# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: algebraic-topology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] Although algebraic topology primarily uses algebra to study topological problems, using topology to solve algebraic problems is sometimes also possible.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] Algebraic topology, for example, allows for a convenient proof that any subgroup of a free group is again a free group.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] In mathematics, homotopy groups are used in algebraic topology to classify topological spaces.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] The first and simplest homotopy group is the fundamental group, which records information about loops in a space.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] Intuitively, homotopy groups record information about the basic shape, or holes, of a topological space.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] In algebraic topology and abstract algebra, **homology** (in part from Greek ὁμός *homos* "identical") is a certain general procedure to associate a sequence of abelian groups or modules with a given mathematical object such as a topological space or a group.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] In homology theory and algebraic topology, **cohomology** is a general term for a sequence of abelian groups defined from a cochain complex.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] That is, cohomology is defined as the abstract study of **cochains**, cocycles, and coboundaries.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] Cohomology can be viewed as a method of assigning algebraic invariants to a topological space that has a more refined algebraic structure than does homology.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] Cohomology arises from the algebraic dualization of the construction of homology.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] In less abstract language, cochains in the fundamental sense should assign "quantities" to the *chains* of homology theory.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] A **manifold** is a topological space that near each point resembles Euclidean space.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] Examples include the plane, the sphere, and the torus, which can all be realized in three dimensions, but also the Klein bottle and real projective plane which cannot be embedded in three dimensions, but can be embedded in four dimensions.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] Typically, results in algebraic topology focus on global, non-differentiable aspects of manifolds; for example Poincaré duality.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] A **simplicial complex** is a topological space of a certain kind, constructed by "gluing together" points, line segments, triangles, and their *n*-dimensional counterparts (see illustration).
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] Simplicial complexes should not be confused with the more abstract notion of a simplicial set appearing in modern simplicial homotopy theory.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] The purely combinatorial counterpart to a simplicial complex is an abstract simplicial complex.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] A **CW complex** is a type of topological space introduced by J.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] Whitehead to meet the needs of homotopy theory.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] This class of spaces is broader and has some better categorical properties than simplicial complexes, but still retains a combinatorial nature that allows for computation (often with a much smaller complex).
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] An older name for the subject was combinatorial topology, implying an emphasis on how a space X was constructed from simpler ones (the modern standard tool for such construction is the CW complex).
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] In the 1920s and 1930s, there was growing emphasis on investigating topological spaces by finding correspondences from them to algebraic groups, which led to the change of name to algebraic topology.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] The combinatorial topology name is still sometimes used to emphasize an algorithmic approach based on decomposition of spaces.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] In the algebraic approach, one finds a correspondence between spaces and groups that respects the relation of homeomorphism (or more general homotopy) of spaces.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] This allows one to recast statements about topological spaces into statements about groups, which have a great deal of manageable structure, often making these statements easier to prove.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] Two major ways in which this can be done are through fundamental groups, or more generally homotopy theory, and through homology and cohomology groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] The fundamental groups give us basic information about the structure of a topological space, but they are often nonabelian and can be difficult to work with.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] The fundamental group of a (finite) simplicial complex does have a finite presentation.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] Homology and cohomology groups, on the other hand, are abelian and in many important cases finitely generated.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] Finitely generated abelian groups are completely classified and are particularly easy to work with.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] In general, all constructions of algebraic topology are functorial; the notions of category, functor and natural transformation originated here.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] One of the first mathematicians to work with different types of cohomology was Georges de Rham.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] One can use the differential structure of smooth manifolds via de Rham cohomology, or Čech or sheaf cohomology to investigate the solvability of differential equations defined on the manifold in question.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] De Rham showed that all of these approaches were interrelated and that, for a closed, oriented manifold, the Betti numbers derived through simplicial homology were the same Betti numbers as those derived through de Rham cohomology.
[src:algebraic-topology/algebraic-topology] This was extended in the 1950s, when Samuel Eilenberg and Norman Steenrod generalized this approach.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In mathematics, specifically in homology theory and algebraic topology, **cohomology** is a way of attaching algebraic invariants to a topological space or other mathematical object that encode its properties in a way that is often computable.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Cohomology is often related to questions of whether some local property of the space is obstructed when passing to a global property.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] For example, the Möbius strip is not the product space of a line segment with a circle (i.e., a cylinder), but locally on any segment of the circle it resembles an ordinary rectangle (product of two line segments) without the global twist.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] The obstruction to making the product structure global is encoded in the first cohomology of the underlying circle, which classifies the two inequivalent ways a line can twist around a circle (an even number of twists or an odd number of twists).
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] The fact that there are only two inequivalent ways of twisting a line around a circle is encoded in the relevant cohomology group $H^{1}(S^{1},\{+1,-1\})$ which can be computed as isomorphic to the group $\{+1,-1\}$ where $+1$ corresponds to an even number of twists, and $-1$ to an odd number.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In its general abstract formulation, cohomology is a sequence of abelian groups often defined from a cochain complex.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Cohomology can be viewed as a method of assigning richer algebraic invariants to a space than homology.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Some versions of cohomology arise by dualizing the construction of homology.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] From its start in topology, this idea became a dominant method in the mathematics of the second half of the twentieth century.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] From the initial idea of homology as a method of constructing algebraic invariants of topological spaces, the range of applications of homology and cohomology theories has spread throughout geometry and algebra.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] The terminology tends to hide the fact that cohomology, a contravariant theory, is more natural than homology in many applications.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] At a basic level, this has to do with functions and pullbacks in geometric situations: given spaces X and Y , and some function F on Y , for any mapping $f:X\to Y$ , composition with F gives rise to a function $F\circ f$ on X .
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] The most important cohomology theories have a product, the cup product, which gives them a ring structure.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Because of this feature, cohomology is usually a stronger invariant than homology.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Cohomology is a family of related constructions that occur in several areas of mathematics.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] The common pattern is that one has objects called *cochains*, a coboundary operator measuring the failure of a cochain to satisfy a compatibility condition, and *cohomology classes* obtained by identifying cochains that differ by a trivial or exact contribution.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] A simple example is the de Rham cohomology of the circle.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] One considers here smooth functions on the circle, which can be thought of as periodic functions $f:\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R}$ , such that $f(\theta +2\pi )=f(\theta )$ for all x .
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] (Here we are parametrizing the functions by radian measure around the unit circle.) The differential of a function $f(\theta )$ is defined by the expression $df(\theta )=f'(\theta )d\theta$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Differentials of a periodic function have the property that their integral over a whole period is zero: by the fundamental theorem of calculus, $\int _{0}^{2\pi }f'(\theta )d\theta =f(2\pi )-f(0)=0$ , because f is periodic over the circle.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] A differential $df(\theta )$ is sometimes called an exact differential.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Another type of differential can also be considered, which is not necessarily exact.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] This does not have an integral of zero over a whole period.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] So the differential $d\theta$ is inexact.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Any differential form $g(\theta )d\theta$ , with $g(\theta )$ appropriately periodic is a differential on the circle.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Indeed, in the latter case we can write $g(\theta )=f'(\theta )$ where $f(\theta )=\int _{0}^{\theta }g(t)\,dt$ , the key point being that $f(\theta )$ is *periodic* (and so defines a function on the circle).
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Moreover, any differential $g(\theta )d\theta$ can be made exact by subtracting from it $C\,d\theta$ where $C={\frac {1}{2\pi }}\int _{0}^{2\pi }g(\theta )d\theta$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] What we have therefore shown is that, although there are many differentials on the circle (exact or inexact), the *quotient space* of inexact differentials *modulo* exact differentials is one-dimensional, parametrized by the constant differential $C\,d\theta$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Here the coboundaries are the exact differentials and the cochains are all differentials.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] The quotient of cochains modulo coboundaries is one-dimensional.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] That is, the first de Rham cohomology group of the circle is isomorphic to the real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ (as an additive group), $H^{1}(S^{1},\mathbb {R} )\cong \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] The circle, being one dimensional, has this one positive cohomology group.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Its only other cohomology group $H^{0}(S^{1},\mathbb {R} )$ consists of functions whose differential is zero, i.e., constants.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Cohomology generalizes this basic setup to higher dimensions and other situations.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Elements of $\ker(d^{n})$ are called cocycles, elements of $\operatorname {im} (d^{n-1})$ are called coboundaries, and elements of the quotient group are called cohomology classes.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In the case of the example of the de Rham cohomology of the circle, $C^{0}$ is all smooth periodic functions, $d^{0}$ is the differential of a function, $C^{1}$ is all differentials $g(\theta )d\theta$ where g is smooth and periodic, and all higher $C^{i}$ and $d^{i}$ are zero.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] One informal way to understand cohomology is that cocycles are locally or formally consistent data, while coboundaries are data that arise from a more elementary choice.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] The cohomology group measures the part of the consistent data that cannot be removed in this way.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] For this reason, cohomology often appears in questions about whether local data can be glued globally, whether a construction can be lifted or extended, or whether two objects that look locally equivalent are globally different.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] This interpretation is especially explicit in sheaf cohomology, where cohomology measures the failure of local sections of a sheaf to glue to global sections.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In more detail, $C_{i}$ is the free abelian group on the set of continuous maps from the standard i -simplex to X (called "singular i -simplices in X "), and $\partial _{i}$ is the i -th boundary homomorphism.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] The groups $C_{i}$ are zero for i negative.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] For an integer i , the i th **cohomology group** of X with coefficients in A is defined to be $\operatorname {ker} (d_{i})/\operatorname {im} (d_{i-1})$ and denoted by $H^{i}(X,A)$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] The group $H^{i}(X,A)$ is zero for i negative.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] The elements of $C_{i}^{*}$ are called **singular i -cochains** with coefficients in A .
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In what follows, the coefficient group A is sometimes not written.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] It is common to take A to be a commutative ring R ; then the cohomology groups are R -modules.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] A standard choice is the ring $\mathbb {Z}$ of integers.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] On the other hand, cohomology has a crucial structure that homology does not: for any topological space X and commutative ring R , there is a bilinear map, called the **cup product**: $H^{i}(X,R)\times H^{j}(X,R)\to H^{i+j}(X,R),$ defined by an explicit formula on singular cochains.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] The product of cohomology classes u and v is written as $u\cup v$ or simply as $uv$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] This product makes the direct sum $H^{*}(X,R)=\bigoplus _{i}H^{i}(X,R)$ into a graded ring, called the **cohomology ring** of X .
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] For any continuous map $f\colon X\to Y,$ the pullback $f^{*}:H^{*}(Y,R)\to H^{*}(X,R)$ is a homomorphism of graded R -algebras.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] It follows that if two spaces are homotopy equivalent, then their cohomology rings are isomorphic.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Here are some of the geometric interpretations of the cup product.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In what follows, manifolds are understood to be without boundary, unless stated otherwise.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] A closed manifold means a compact manifold (without boundary), whereas a closed *submanifold* *N* of a manifold *M* means a submanifold that is a closed subset of *M*, not necessarily compact (although *N* is automatically compact if *M* is).
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Very informally, for any topological space *X*, elements of $H^{i}(X)$ can be thought of as represented by codimension-*i* subspaces of *X* that can move freely on *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] For example, one way to define an element of $H^{i}(X)$ is to give a continuous map *f* from *X* to a manifold *M* and a closed codimension-*i* submanifold *N* of *M* with an orientation on the normal bundle.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In what follows, cohomology is taken with coefficients in the integers **Z**, unless stated otherwise.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] The cup product on cohomology can be viewed as coming from the diagonal map $\Delta :X\to X\times X$ , $x\mapsto (x,x)$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Namely, for any spaces X and Y with cohomology classes $u\in H^{i}(X,R)$ and $v\in H^{j}(Y,R)$ , there is an **external product** (or **cross product**) cohomology class $u\times v\in H^{i+j}(X\times Y,R)$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Alternatively, the external product can be defined in terms of the cup product.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] For spaces X and Y , write $f:X\times Y\to X$ and $g:X\times Y\to Y$ for the two projections.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Another interpretation of Poincaré duality is that the cohomology ring of a closed oriented manifold is self-dual in a strong sense.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Namely, let X be a closed connected oriented manifold of dimension n , and let F be a field.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] is a perfect pairing for each integer i .
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In particular, the vector spaces $H^{i}(X,F)$ and $H^{n-i}(X,F)$ have the same (finite) dimension.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Likewise, the product on integral cohomology modulo torsion with values in $H^{n}(X,\mathbb {Z} )\cong \mathbb {Z}$ is a perfect pairing over $\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] An oriented real vector bundle *E* of rank *r* over a topological space *X* determines a cohomology class on *X*, the **Euler class** χ(*E*) ∈ *H**r*(*X*,**Z**).
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Informally, the Euler class is the class of the zero set of a general section of *E*.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] That interpretation can be made more explicit when *E* is a smooth vector bundle over a smooth manifold *X*, since then a general smooth section of *X* vanishes on a codimension-*r* submanifold of *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] There are several other types of characteristic classes for vector bundles that take values in cohomology, including Chern classes, Stiefel–Whitney classes, and Pontryagin classes.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] For each abelian group *A* and natural number *j*, there is a space $K(A,j)$ whose *j*-th homotopy group is isomorphic to *A* and whose other homotopy groups are zero.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Such a space is called an **Eilenberg–MacLane space**.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] This space has the remarkable property that it is a **classifying space** for cohomology: there is a natural element *u* of $H^{j}(K(A,j),A)$ , and every cohomology class of degree *j* on every space *X* is the pullback of *u* by some continuous map $X\to K(A,j)$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] for every space *X* with the homotopy type of a CW complex.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Here $[X,Y]$ denotes the set of homotopy classes of continuous maps from *X* to *Y*.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] For example, the space $K(\mathbb {Z} ,1)$ (defined up to homotopy equivalence) can be taken to be the circle $S^{1}$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] So the description above says that every element of $H^{1}(X,\mathbb {Z} )$ is pulled back from the class *u* of a point on $S^{1}$ by some map $X\to S^{1}$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] There is a related description of the first cohomology with coefficients in any abelian group *A*, say for a CW complex *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Namely, $H^{1}(X,A)$ is in one-to-one correspondence with the set of isomorphism classes of Galois covering spaces of *X* with group *A*, also called principal *A*-bundles over *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] For *X* connected, it follows that $H^{1}(X,A)$ is isomorphic to $\operatorname {Hom} (\pi _{1}(X),A)$ , where $\pi _{1}(X)$ is the fundamental group of *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] For example, $H^{1}(X,\mathbb {Z} /2)$ classifies the double covering spaces of *X*, with the element $0\in H^{1}(X,\mathbb {Z} /2)$ corresponding to the trivial double covering, the disjoint union of two copies of *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] for any integers *i* and *j* and any commutative ring *R*.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] makes the singular homology of *X* into a module over the singular cohomology ring of *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] which is an isomorphism for *R* a field.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] For example, let *X* be an oriented manifold, not necessarily compact.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Then a closed oriented codimension-*i* submanifold *Y* of *X* (not necessarily compact) determines an element of *H**i*(*X*,*R*), and a compact oriented *j*-dimensional submanifold *Z* of *X* determines an element of *H**j*(*X*,*R*).
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] The cap product [*Y*] ∩ [*Z*] ∈ *H**j*−*i*(*X*,*R*) can be computed by perturbing *Y* and *Z* to make them intersect transversely and then taking the class of their intersection, which is a compact oriented submanifold of dimension *j* − *i*.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] A closed oriented manifold *X* of dimension *n* has a fundamental class [*X*] in *H**n*(*X*,*R*).
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] The Poincaré duality isomorphism $H^{i}(X,R){\overset {\cong }{\to }}H_{n-i}(X,R)$ is defined by cap product with the fundamental class of *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Although cohomology is fundamental to modern algebraic topology, its importance was not seen for some 40 years after the development of homology.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] The concept of *dual cell structure*, which Henri Poincaré used in his proof of his Poincaré duality theorem, contained the beginning of the idea of cohomology, but this was not seen until later.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] There were various precursors to cohomology.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Alexander and Solomon Lefschetz founded intersection theory of cycles on manifolds.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] On a closed oriented *n*-dimensional manifold *M* an *i*-cycle and a *j*-cycle with nonempty intersection will, if in the general position, have as their intersection a (*i* + *j* − *n*)-cycle.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] which (in retrospect) can be identified with the cup product on the cohomology of *M*.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Alexander had by 1930 defined a first notion of a cochain, by thinking of an *i*-cochain on a space *X* as a function on small neighborhoods of the diagonal in *X**i*+1.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In 1931, Georges de Rham related homology and differential forms, proving de Rham's theorem.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] This result can be stated more simply in terms of cohomology.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In 1932–33, cohomology essentially appeared in works of Heinz Hopf and Egbert van Kampen on obstructions.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Hopf invented an obstruction to homotopy (and homotopy classification) of continuous maps from a *k*-dimensional polyhedron to the *k*-dimensional sphere.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In his work cohomology appeared implicitly, and the more natural formulation explicitly involving cohomology was given by Hassler Whitney in 1937.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Van Kampen invented an obstruction to (and, for *k>2*, a criterion for) embeddability of a *k*-dimensional polyhedron to the *2k*-dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In his work cohomology appeared explicitly, but only for a particular case (of certain configuration space, the deleted product).
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In 1934, Lev Pontryagin proved the Pontryagin duality theorem; a result on topological groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] This (in rather special cases) provided an interpretation of Poincaré duality and Alexander duality in terms of group characters.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] At a 1935 conference in Moscow, Andrey Kolmogorov and Alexander both introduced cohomology and tried to construct a cohomology product structure.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In 1936, Norman Steenrod constructed Čech cohomology by dualizing Čech homology.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] From 1936 to 1938, Hassler Whitney and Eduard Čech developed the cup product (making cohomology into a graded ring) and cap product, and realized that Poincaré duality can be stated in terms of the cap product.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Their theory was still limited to finite cell complexes.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In 1944, Samuel Eilenberg overcame the technical limitations, and gave the modern definition of singular homology and cohomology.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In 1945, Eilenberg and Steenrod stated the axioms defining a homology or cohomology theory, discussed below.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In their 1952 book, *Foundations of Algebraic Topology*, they proved that the existing homology and cohomology theories did indeed satisfy their axioms.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In 1946, Jean Leray defined sheaf cohomology.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In 1948 Edwin Spanier, building on work of Alexander and Kolmogorov, developed Alexander–Spanier cohomology.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Grothendieck elegantly defined and characterized sheaf cohomology in the language of homological algebra.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] The essential point is to fix the space *X* and think of sheaf cohomology as a functor from the abelian category of sheaves on *X* to abelian groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Start with the functor taking a sheaf *E* on *X* to its abelian group of global sections over *X*, *E*(*X*).
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] This functor is left exact, but not necessarily right exact.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Grothendieck defined sheaf cohomology groups to be the right derived functors of the left exact functor *E* ↦ *E*(*X*).
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] That definition suggests various generalizations.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] For example, one can define the cohomology of a topological space *X* with coefficients in any complex of sheaves, earlier called hypercohomology (but usually now just "cohomology").
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] From that point of view, sheaf cohomology becomes a sequence of functors from the derived category of sheaves on *X* to abelian groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In a broad sense of the word, "cohomology" is often used for the right derived functors of a left exact functor on an abelian category, while "homology" is used for the left derived functors of a right exact functor.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] For example, for a ring *R*, the Tor groups Tor*i**R*(*M*,*N*) form a "homology theory" in each variable, the left derived functors of the tensor product *M*⊗*R**N* of *R*-modules.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Likewise, the Ext groups Ext*i**R*(*M*,*N*) can be viewed as a "cohomology theory" in each variable, the right derived functors of the Hom functor Hom*R*(*M*,*N*).
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Sheaf cohomology can be identified with a type of Ext group.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Namely, for a sheaf *E* on a topological space *X*, *H**i*(*X*,*E*) is isomorphic to Ext*i*(**Z***X*, *E*), where **Z***X* denotes the constant sheaf associated with the integers **Z**, and Ext is taken in the abelian category of sheaves on *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] There are numerous machines built for computing the cohomology of algebraic varieties.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] The simplest case being the determination of cohomology for smooth projective varieties over a field of characteristic 0 .
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Tools from Hodge theory, called Hodge structures, help give computations of cohomology of these types of varieties (with the addition of more refined information).
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In the simplest case the cohomology of a smooth hypersurface in $\mathbb {P} ^{n}$ can be determined from the degree of the polynomial alone.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] When considering varieties over a finite field, or a field of characteristic p , more powerful tools are required because the classical definitions of homology/cohomology break down.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] This is because varieties over finite fields will only be a finite set of points.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Grothendieck came up with the idea for a Grothendieck topology and used sheaf cohomology over the étale topology to define the cohomology theory for varieties over a finite field.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Using the étale topology for a variety over a field of characteristic p one can construct $\ell$ -adic cohomology for $\ell \neq p$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] then there is an equality of dimensions for the Betti cohomology of $X(\mathbb {C} )$ and the $\ell$ -adic cohomology of $X(\mathbb {F} _{q})$ whenever the variety is smooth over both fields.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In addition to these cohomology theories there are other cohomology theories called Weil cohomology theories which behave similarly to singular cohomology.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] There is a conjectured theory of motives which underlie all of the Weil cohomology theories.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Another useful computational tool is the blowup sequence.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] There are various ways to define cohomology for topological spaces (such as singular cohomology, Čech cohomology, Alexander–Spanier cohomology or sheaf cohomology).
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] (Here sheaf cohomology is considered only with coefficients in a constant sheaf.) These theories give different answers for some spaces, but there is a large class of spaces on which they all agree.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] This is most easily understood axiomatically: there is a list of properties known as the Eilenberg–Steenrod axioms, and any two constructions that share those properties will agree at least on all CW complexes.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] There are versions of the axioms for a homology theory as well as for a cohomology theory.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Some theories can be viewed as tools for computing singular cohomology for special topological spaces, such as simplicial cohomology for simplicial complexes, cellular cohomology for CW complexes, and de Rham cohomology for smooth manifolds.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] One of the Eilenberg–Steenrod axioms for a cohomology theory is the **dimension axiom**: if *P* is a single point, then *Hi*(*P*) = 0 for all *i* ≠ 0.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Whitehead observed that it is fruitful to omit the dimension axiom completely: this gives the notion of a generalized homology theory or a generalized cohomology theory, defined below.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] There are generalized cohomology theories such as K-theory or complex cobordism that give rich information about a topological space, not directly accessible from singular cohomology.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] The axioms for a generalized cohomology theory are obtained by reversing the arrows, roughly speaking.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] A spectrum determines both a generalized homology theory and a generalized cohomology theory.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] A fundamental result by Brown, Whitehead, and Adams says that every generalized homology theory comes from a spectrum, and likewise every generalized cohomology theory comes from a spectrum.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] This generalizes the representability of ordinary cohomology by Eilenberg–MacLane spaces.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Likewise, the functor from the stable homotopy category to generalized cohomology theories on CW-pairs is not an equivalence.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] It is the stable homotopy category, not these other categories, that has good properties such as being triangulated.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] If one prefers homology or cohomology theories to be defined on all topological spaces rather than on CW complexes, one standard approach is to include the axiom that every weak homotopy equivalence induces an isomorphism on homology or cohomology.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] (That is true for singular homology or singular cohomology, but not for sheaf cohomology, for example.) Since every space admits a weak homotopy equivalence from a CW complex, this axiom reduces homology or cohomology theories on all spaces to the corresponding theory on CW complexes.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] Many of these theories carry richer information than ordinary cohomology, but are harder to compute.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] A cohomology theory *E* is said to be **multiplicative** if $E^{*}(X)$ has the structure of a graded ring for each space *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/cohomology] In the language of spectra, there are several more precise notions of a ring spectrum, such as an *E*∞ ring spectrum, where the product is commutative and associative in a strong sense.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] In mathematics, and specifically in topology, a **CW complex** (also **cellular complex** or **cell complex**) is a topological space that is built by gluing together topological balls (so-called *cells*) of different dimensions in specific ways.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] The notion generalizes both manifolds and simplicial complexes and has particular significance for algebraic topology.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] CW complexes have better categorical properties than simplicial complexes, but still retain a combinatorial nature that allows for computation (often with a much smaller complex).
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] The C in CW stands for "closure-finite", and the W for "weak" topology.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] The maps are also called attaching maps.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] Each $X_{k}$ is called the **k-skeleton** of the complex.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] The topology of $X=\cup _{k}X_{k}$ is a **weak topology**: a subset $U\subset X$ is open iff $U\cap X_{k}$ is open for each k-skeleton $X_{k}$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] This partition of *X* is also called a **cellulation**.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] A **regular CW complex** is a CW complex whose gluing maps are homeomorphisms.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] Accordingly, the partition of *X* is also called a **regular cellulation**.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] A loopless graph is represented by a regular 1-dimensional CW-complex.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] A closed 2-cell graph embedding on a surface is a regular 2-dimensional CW-complex.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] Finally, the 3-sphere regular cellulation conjecture claims that every 2-connected graph is the 1-skeleton of a regular CW-complex on the 3-dimensional sphere.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] Roughly speaking, a *relative CW complex* differs from a CW complex in that we allow it to have one extra building block that does not necessarily possess a cellular structure.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] This extra-block can be treated as a (−1)-dimensional cell in the former definition.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] Every discrete topological space is a 0-dimensional CW complex.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] Singular homology and cohomology of CW complexes is readily computable via cellular homology.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] Moreover, in the category of CW complexes and cellular maps, cellular homology can be interpreted as a homology theory.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] To compute an extraordinary (co)homology theory for a CW complex, the Atiyah–Hirzebruch spectral sequence is the analogue of cellular homology.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] Both of the above examples are particularly simple because the homology is determined by the number of cells—i.e.: the cellular attaching maps have no role in these computations.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] This is a very special phenomenon and is not indicative of the general case.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] There is a technique, developed by Whitehead, for replacing a CW complex with a homotopy-equivalent CW complex that has a *simpler* CW decomposition.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] Consider, for example, an arbitrary CW complex.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] Its 1-skeleton can be fairly complicated, being an arbitrary graph.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] Now consider a maximal forest *F* in this graph.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] Since it is a collection of trees, and trees are contractible, consider the space $X/{\sim }$ where the equivalence relation is generated by $x\sim y$ if they are contained in a common tree in the maximal forest *F*.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] The quotient map $X\to X/{\sim }$ is a homotopy equivalence.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] Moreover, $X/{\sim }$ naturally inherits a CW structure, with cells corresponding to the cells of X that are not contained in *F*.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] In particular, the 1-skeleton of $X/{\sim }$ is a disjoint union of wedges of circles.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] Another way of stating the above is that a connected CW complex can be replaced by a homotopy-equivalent CW complex whose 0-skeleton consists of a single point.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] Consider climbing up the connectivity ladder—assume *X* is a simply-connected CW complex whose 0-skeleton consists of a point.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] Can we, through suitable modifications, replace *X* by a homotopy-equivalent CW complex where $X^{1}$ consists of a single point?
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] The first step is to observe that $X^{1}$ and the attaching maps to construct $X^{2}$ from $X^{1}$ form a group presentation.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] The Tietze theorem for group presentations states that there is a sequence of moves we can perform to reduce this group presentation to the trivial presentation of the trivial group.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] If a CW complex *X* is *n*-connected one can find a homotopy-equivalent CW complex ${\tilde {X}}$ whose *n*-skeleton $X^{n}$ consists of a single point.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] The homotopy category of CW complexes is, in the opinion of some experts, the best if not the only candidate for *the* homotopy category (for technical reasons the version for pointed spaces is actually used).
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] Auxiliary constructions that yield spaces that are not CW complexes must be used on occasion.
[src:algebraic-topology/cw-complex] One basic result is that the representable functors on the homotopy category have a simple characterisation (the Brown representability theorem).
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] In the mathematical field of algebraic topology, the **fundamental group** of a topological space is the group of the equivalence classes under homotopy of the loops contained in the space.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] It records information about the basic shape, or holes, of the topological space.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group is the first and simplest homotopy group.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group is a homotopy invariant—topological spaces that are homotopy equivalent (or the stronger case of homeomorphic) have isomorphic fundamental groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group of a topological space X is denoted by $\pi _{1}(X)$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Start with a space (for example, a surface), and some point in it, and all the loops both starting and ending at this point—paths that start at this point, wander around and eventually return to the starting point.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Two loops can be combined in an obvious way: travel along the first loop, then along the second.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Two loops are considered equivalent if one can be deformed into the other without breaking.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The set of all such loops with this method of combining and this equivalence between them is the fundamental group for that particular space.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Henri Poincaré defined the fundamental group in 1895 in his paper "Analysis situs".
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The concept emerged in the theory of Riemann surfaces, in the work of Bernhard Riemann, Poincaré, and Felix Klein.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] It describes the monodromy properties of complex-valued functions, as well as providing a complete topological classification of closed surfaces.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Throughout this article, X is a topological space.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] A typical example is a surface such as the one depicted at the right.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Moreover, $x_{0}$ is a point in X called the *base-point*.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] (As is explained below, its role is rather auxiliary.) The idea of the definition of the homotopy group is to measure how many (broadly speaking) curves on X can be deformed into each other.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The precise definition depends on the notion of the homotopy of loops, which is explained first.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] such that the starting point $\gamma (0)$ and the end point $\gamma (1)$ are both equal to $x_{0}$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] A *homotopy* is a continuous interpolation between two loops.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] If such a homotopy h exists, $\gamma$ and $\gamma '$ are said to be *homotopic*.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The purpose of considering the equivalence classes of loops up to homotopy, as opposed to the set of all loops (the so-called loop space of X ) is that the latter, while being useful for various purposes, is a rather big and unwieldy object.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] By contrast the above quotient is, in many cases, more manageable and computable.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] By the above definition, $\pi _{1}(X,x_{0})$ is just a set.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] It becomes a group (and therefore deserves the name fundamental *group*) using the concatenation of loops.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Thus the loop $\gamma _{0}\cdot \gamma _{1}$ first follows the loop $\gamma _{0}$ with "twice the speed" and then follows $\gamma _{1}$ with "twice the speed".
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The product of two homotopy classes of loops $[\gamma _{0}]$ and $[\gamma _{1}]$ is then defined as $[\gamma _{0}\cdot \gamma _{1}]$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] It can be shown that this product does not depend on the choice of representatives and therefore gives a well-defined operation on the set $\pi _{1}(X,x_{0})$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] This operation turns $\pi _{1}(X,x_{0})$ into a group.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Its neutral element is the equivalence (homotopy) class of the constant loop, which stays at $x_{0}$ for all times t (i.e. this class consists of all loops that can be continuously deformed into the constant loop; intuitively speaking of all the loops that do not "wrap around a hole").
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The inverse of a (homotopy class of a) loop is the same loop, but traversed in the opposite direction (which is in a different homotopy class).
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] is the concatenation of these loops, traversing $\gamma _{0}$ and then $\gamma _{1}$ with quadruple speed, and then $\gamma _{2}$ with double speed.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] traverses the same paths (in the same order), but $\gamma _{0}$ with double speed, and $\gamma _{1},\gamma _{2}$ with quadruple speed.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Thus, because of the differing speeds, the two paths are not identical.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] therefore crucially depends on the fact that paths are considered up to homotopy.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Indeed, both above composites are homotopic, for example, to the loop that traverses all three loops $\gamma _{0},\gamma _{1},\gamma _{2}$ with triple speed.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The set of based loops up to homotopy, equipped with the above operation therefore does turn $\pi _{1}(X,x_{0})$ into a group.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] This isomorphism is, in general, not unique: it depends on the choice of path up to homotopy.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] However changing the path results in changing the isomorphism between the two fundamental groups only by composition with an inner automorphism.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] It is therefore customary to write $\pi _{1}(X)$ instead of $\pi _{1}(X,x_{0})$ when the choice of basepoint does not matter.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] This section lists some basic examples of fundamental groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] To begin with, in Euclidean space ( $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ) or any convex subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{n},$ there is only one homotopy class of loops, and the fundamental group is therefore the trivial group with one element.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] More generally, any star domain – and yet more generally, any contractible space – has a trivial fundamental group.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Thus, the fundamental group does not distinguish between such spaces.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] A path-connected space whose fundamental group is trivial is called simply connected.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] For example, the 2-sphere $S^{2}=\left\{(x,y,z)\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}\mid x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}=1\right\}$ depicted on the right, and also all the higher-dimensional spheres, are simply-connected.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The figure illustrates a homotopy contracting one particular loop to the constant loop.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Instead, each homotopy class consists of all loops that wind around the circle a given number of times (which can be positive or negative, depending on the direction of winding).
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The product of a loop that winds around m times and another that winds around n times is a loop that winds around $m+n$ times.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Therefore, the fundamental group of the circle is isomorphic to $(\mathbb {Z} ,+),$ the additive group of integers.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] This fact can be used to give proofs of the Brouwer fixed point theorem and the Borsuk–Ulam theorem in dimension 2.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group of the figure eight is the free group on two letters.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] More generally, the fundamental group of a bouquet of r circles is the free group on r letters.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group of a wedge sum of two path connected spaces X and Y can be computed as the free product of the individual fundamental groups: $\pi _{1}(X\vee Y)\cong \pi _{1}(X)*\pi _{1}(Y)$ This generalizes the above observations since the figure eight is the wedge sum of two circles.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group of the plane punctured at n points is also the free group with n generators.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The i -th generator is the class of the loop that goes around the i -th puncture without going around any other punctures.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group can be defined for discrete structures too.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] In particular, consider a connected graph $G=(V,E)$ , with a designated vertex $v_{0}$ in V .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The loops in G are the cycles that start and end at $v_{0}$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Every simple loop in G contains exactly one edge in $E\setminus T$ ; every loop in G is a concatenation of such simple loops.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Therefore, the fundamental group of a graph is a free group, in which the number of generators is exactly the number of edges in $E\setminus T$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] For example, suppose G has 16 vertices arranged in 4 rows of 4 vertices each, with edges connecting vertices that are adjacent horizontally or vertically.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Then G has 24 edges overall, and the number of edges in each spanning tree is 16 − 1 = 15, so the fundamental group of G is the free group with 9 generators.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Note that G has 9 "holes", similarly to a bouquet of 9 circles, which has the same fundamental group.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group of a topological group X (with respect to the base point being the neutral element) is always commutative.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] In particular, the fundamental group of a Lie group is commutative.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] This binary operation $\star$ on the set of all loops is *a priori* independent from the one described above.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] However, the Eckmann–Hilton argument shows that it does in fact agree with the above concatenation of loops, and moreover that the resulting group structure is abelian.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] An inspection of the proof shows that, more generally, $\pi _{1}(X)$ is abelian for any H-space X , i.e., the multiplication need not have an inverse, nor does it have to be associative.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] For example, this shows that the fundamental group of a loop space of another topological space Y , $X=\Omega (Y),$ is abelian.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Related ideas lead to Heinz Hopf's computation of the cohomology of a Lie group.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] This mapping from continuous maps to group homomorphisms is compatible with composition of maps and identity morphisms.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] from the category of topological spaces together with a base point to the category of groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] It turns out that this functor does not distinguish maps that are homotopic relative to the base point: if $f,g:X\to Y$ are continuous maps with $f(x_{0})=g(x_{0})=y_{0}$ , and f and g are homotopic relative to $\{x_{0}\}$ , then $f_{*}=g_{*}$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] is a homotopy equivalence and therefore yields an isomorphism of their fundamental groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group functor takes products to products and coproducts to coproducts.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] (In the latter formula, $\vee$ denotes the wedge sum of pointed topological spaces, and * the free product of groups.) The latter formula is a special case of the Seifert–van Kampen theorem, which states that the fundamental group functor takes pushouts along inclusions to pushouts.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] As was mentioned above, computing the fundamental group of even relatively simple topological spaces tends to be not entirely trivial, but requires some methods of algebraic topology.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The abelianization of the fundamental group can be identified with the first homology group of the space.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] A special case of the Hurewicz theorem asserts that the first singular homology group $H_{1}(X)$ is, colloquially speaking, the closest approximation to the fundamental group by means of an abelian group.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] from the fundamental group of a topological space X to its first singular homology group $H_{1}(X).$ This homomorphism is not in general an isomorphism since the fundamental group may be non-abelian, but the homology group is, by definition, always abelian.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] This difference is, however, the only one: if X is path-connected, this homomorphism is surjective and its kernel is the commutator subgroup of the fundamental group, so that $H_{1}(X)$ is isomorphic to the abelianization of the fundamental group.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] For example, the 2-sphere $S^{2}$ can be obtained by gluing two copies of slightly overlapping half-spheres along a neighborhood of the equator.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] In this case the theorem yields $\pi _{1}(S^{2})$ is trivial, since the two half-spheres are contractible and therefore have trivial fundamental group.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental groups of surfaces, as mentioned above, can also be computed using this theorem.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] In the parlance of category theory, the theorem can be concisely stated by saying that the fundamental group functor takes pushouts (in the category of topological spaces) along inclusions to pushouts (in the category of groups).
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] A covering is called a universal covering if E is, in addition to the preceding condition, simply connected.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] It is universal in the sense that all other coverings can be constructed by suitably identifying points in E .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] (or, equivalently, $\pi :\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} /\mathbb {Z} ,\ t\mapsto [t]$ ) is a universal covering.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Any path connected, locally path connected and locally simply connected topological space X admits a universal covering.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] An abstract construction proceeds analogously to the fundamental group by taking pairs $(x,\gamma )$ , where x is a point in X and $\gamma$ is a homotopy class of paths from $x_{0}$ to x .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The passage from a topological space to its universal covering can be used in understanding the geometry of X .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] For example, the uniformization theorem shows that any simply connected Riemann surface is (isomorphic to) either $S^{2},$ $\mathbb {C} ,$ or the upper half-plane.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] General Riemann surfaces then arise as quotients of group actions on these three surfaces.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Let G be a connected, simply connected compact Lie group, for example, the special unitary group ${\text{SU}}(n)$ , and let $\Gamma$ be a finite subgroup of G .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Then the homogeneous space $X=G/\Gamma$ has fundamental group $\Gamma$ , which acts by right multiplication on the universal covering space G .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] In this case the fundamental group is $\Gamma$ and the universal covering space $G/K$ is actually contractible (by the Cartan decomposition for Lie groups).
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] As an example take $G={\text{SL}}(2,\mathbb {R} )$ , $K={\text{SO}}(2)$ and $\Gamma$ any torsion-free congruence subgroup of the modular group ${\text{SL}}(2,\mathbb {Z} )$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] From the explicit realization, it also follows that the universal covering space of a path connected topological group H is again a path connected topological group G .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Since G is a connected group with a continuous action by conjugation on a discrete group $\Gamma$ , it must act trivially, so that $\Gamma$ has to be a subgroup of the center of G .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] In particular $\pi _{1}(H)=\Gamma$ is an abelian group; this can also easily be seen directly without using covering spaces.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The group G is called the *universal covering group* of H .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] As the universal covering group suggests, there is an analogy between the fundamental group of a topological group and the center of a group; this is elaborated at Lattice of covering groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] which generalizes the above fact about the universal covering (which amounts to the case where the fiber F is also discrete).
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] What is more, the sequence can be continued at the left with the higher homotopy groups $\pi _{n}$ of the three spaces, which gives some access to computing such groups in the same vein.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group of noncompact Lie groups can be reduced to the compact case, since such a group is homotopic to its maximal compact subgroup.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] A second method of computing fundamental groups applies to all connected compact Lie groups and uses the machinery of the maximal torus and the associated root system.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] can be shown to be surjective with kernel given by the set I of integer linear combination of coroots.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] This method shows, for example, that any connected compact Lie group for which the associated root system is of type $G_{2}$ is simply connected.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Thus, there is (up to isomorphism) only one connected compact Lie group having Lie algebra of type $G_{2}$ ; this group is simply connected and has trivial center.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] When the topological space is homeomorphic to a simplicial complex, its fundamental group can be described explicitly in terms of generators and relations.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] If X is a connected simplicial complex, an *edge-path* in X is defined to be a chain of vertices connected by edges in X .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Two edge-paths are said to be *edge-equivalent* if one can be obtained from the other by successively switching between an edge and the two opposite edges of a triangle in X .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] If v is a fixed vertex in X , an *edge-loop* at v is an edge-path starting and ending at v .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The **edge-path group** $E(X,v)$ is defined to be the set of edge-equivalence classes of edge-loops at v , with product and inverse defined by concatenation and reversal of edge-loops.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The edge-path group is naturally isomorphic to $\pi _{1}(|X|,v)$ , the fundamental group of the geometric realisation $|X|$ of X .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Since it depends only on the 2-skeleton $X^{2}$ of X (that is, the vertices, edges, and triangles of X ), the groups $\pi _{1}(|X|,v)$ and $\pi _{1}(|X^{2}|,v)$ are isomorphic.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The edge-path group can be described explicitly in terms of generators and relations.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] If T is a maximal spanning tree in the 1-skeleton of X , then $E(X,v)$ is canonically isomorphic to the group with generators (the oriented edge-paths of X not occurring in T ) and relations (the edge-equivalences corresponding to triangles in X ).
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] A similar result holds if T is replaced by any simply connected—in particular contractible—subcomplex of X .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] This often gives a practical way of computing fundamental groups and can be used to show that every finitely presented group arises as the fundamental group of a finite simplicial complex.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] It is also one of the classical methods used for topological surfaces, which are classified by their fundamental groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The *universal covering space* of a finite connected simplicial complex X can also be described directly as a simplicial complex using edge-paths.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Its vertices are pairs $(w,\gamma )$ where w is a vertex of X and γ is an edge-equivalence class of paths from v to w .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The k -simplices containing $(w,\gamma )$ correspond naturally to the k -simplices containing w .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Each new vertex u of the k -simplex gives an edge $wu$ and hence, by concatenation, a new path $\gamma _{u}$ from v to u .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The points $(w,\gamma )$ and $(u,\gamma _{u})$ are the vertices of the "transported" simplex in the universal covering space.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The edge-path group acts naturally by concatenation, preserving the simplicial structure, and the quotient space is just X .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] It is well known that this method can also be used to compute the fundamental group of an arbitrary topological space.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] This was doubtless known to Eduard Čech and Jean Leray and explicitly appeared as a remark in a paper by André Weil; various other authors such as Lorenzo Calabi, Wu Wen-tsün, and Nodar Berikashvili have also published proofs.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] In the simplest case of a compact space X with a finite open covering in which all non-empty finite intersections of open sets in the covering are contractible, the fundamental group can be identified with the edge-path group of the simplicial complex corresponding to the nerve of the covering.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Roughly speaking, the fundamental group detects the 1-dimensional hole structure of a space, but not higher-dimensional holes such as for the 2-sphere.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Such "higher-dimensional holes" can be detected using the higher homotopy groups $\pi _{n}(X)$ , which are defined to consist of homotopy classes of (basepoint-preserving) maps from $S^{n}$ to X .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] As was mentioned in the above computation of $\pi _{1}$ of classical Lie groups, higher homotopy groups can be relevant even for computing fundamental groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The *fundamental groupoid* is a variant of the fundamental group that is useful in situations where the choice of a base point $x_{0}\in X$ is undesirable.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] where r is an arbitrary non-negative real number.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Since the length r is variable in this approach, such paths can be concatenated as is (i.e., not up to homotopy) and therefore yield a category.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The category of paths up to this equivalence relation is denoted $\Pi (X).$ Each morphism in $\Pi (X)$ is an isomorphism, with inverse given by the same path traversed in the opposite direction.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Generally speaking, representations may serve to exhibit features of a group by its actions on other mathematical objects, often vector spaces.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Conversely, any such representation on a path-connected space X arises in this manner.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] This equivalence of categories between representations of $\pi _{1}(X)$ and local systems is used, for example, in the study of differential equations, such as the Knizhnik–Zamolodchikov equations.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] In algebraic geometry, the so-called étale fundamental group is used as a replacement for the fundamental group.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Since the Zariski topology on an algebraic variety or scheme X is much coarser than, say, the topology of open subsets in $\mathbb {R} ^{n},$ it is no longer meaningful to consider continuous maps from an interval to X .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Instead, the approach developed by Grothendieck consists in constructing $\pi _{1}^{\text{et}}$ by considering all finite étale covers of X .
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] These serve as an algebro-geometric analogue of coverings with finite fibers.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] This yields a theory applicable in situations where no great generality classical topological intuition whatsoever is available, for example for varieties defined over a finite field.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Also, the étale fundamental group of a field is its (absolute) Galois group.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] On the other hand, for smooth varieties X over the complex numbers, the étale fundamental group retains much of the information inherent in the classical fundamental group: the former is the profinite completion of the latter.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group of a root system is defined in analogy to the computation for Lie groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] This allows to define and use the fundamental group of a semisimple linear algebraic group G , which is a useful basic tool in the classification of linear algebraic groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The homotopy relation between 1-simplices of a simplicial set X is an equivalence relation if X is a Kan complex but not necessarily so in general.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] Thus, $\pi _{1}$ of a Kan complex can be defined as the set of homotopy classes of 1-simplices.
[src:algebraic-topology/fundamental-group] The fundamental group of an arbitrary simplicial set X are defined to be the homotopy group of its topological realization, $|X|,$ i.e., the topological space obtained by gluing topological simplices as prescribed by the simplicial set structure of X .
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] In mathematics, the term **homology**, originally introduced in algebraic topology, has three primary, closely related usages.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] First, there is the *homology of a chain complex*, a sequence of abelian groups, called *homology groups*, which are regarded as fundamental invariants of the chain complex.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Secondly, when one can associate a chain complex to a different mathematical object, one can also associate its homology to that object.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Distinct procedures of associating chain complexes to a given object are grouped into *homology theories*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Finally, homology is important in the study of topological spaces.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Under nice conditions in which distinct homology theories for a single topological space produce the same homology groups, one can define a single *homology of a topological space*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] This last notion of homology is closely related to topological ideas frequently discussed in popular mathematics such as the holes of a surface or the cycles of a graph.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] There is also a related notion of the cohomology of a cochain complex, giving rise to various cohomology theories, in addition to the notion of the cohomology of a topological space.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The n th **homology group** $H_{n}$ of this chain complex is then the quotient group $H_{n}=Z_{n}/B_{n}$ of cycles modulo boundaries.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] One can endow chain complexes with additional structure: for example, taking the groups $C_{n}$ to be modules over a coefficient ring R and taking the boundary maps $d_{n}$ to be R -module homomorphisms results in homology groups $H_{n}$ that are also quotient modules.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Tools from homological algebra can be used to relate homology groups of different chain complexes.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] To associate a *homology theory* to other types of mathematical objects, one first gives a prescription for associating chain complexes to that object, and then takes the homology of such a chain complex.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] For the homology theory to be valid, all such chain complexes associated to the same mathematical object must have the same homology.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The resulting homology theory is often named according to the type of chain complex prescribed.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] For example, singular homology, Morse homology, Khovanov homology, and Hochschild homology are respectively obtained from singular chain complexes, Morse complexes, Khovanov complexes, and Hochschild complexes.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] In other cases, such as for group homology, there are multiple common methods to compute the same homology groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] In the language of category theory, a homology theory is a type of functor from the category of the mathematical object being studied to the category of abelian groups and group homomorphisms, or more generally to the category corresponding to the associated chain complexes.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] One can also formulate homology theories as derived functors on appropriate abelian categories, measuring the failure of an appropriate functor to be exact.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] One can describe this latter construction explicitly in terms of resolutions, or more abstractly from the perspective of derived categories or model categories.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Regardless of how they are formulated, homology theories help provide information about the structure of the mathematical objects to which they are associated, and can sometimes help distinguish different objects.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Perhaps the most familiar usage of the term homology is for the *homology of a topological space*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] For 1-dimensional topological spaces, probably the simplest homology theory to use is graph homology, which could be regarded as a 1-dimensional special case of simplicial homology, the latter of which involves a decomposition of the topological space into simplices.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Replacing simplices with disks of various dimensions results in a related construction called cellular homology.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] There are also other ways of computing these homology groups, for example via Morse homology, or by taking the output of the universal coefficient theorem when applied to a cohomology theory such as Čech cohomology or (in the case of real coefficients) De Rham cohomology.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Studying topological features such as these led to the notion of the *cycles* that represent homology classes (the elements of homology groups).
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] For example, the two embedded circles in a figure-eight shape provide examples of one-dimensional cycles, or 1-cycles, and the 2-torus $T^{2}$ and 2-sphere $S^{2}$ represent 2-cycles.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Cycles form a group under the operation of *formal addition,* which refers to adding cycles symbolically rather than combining them geometrically.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Any formal sum of cycles is again called a cycle.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Explicit constructions of homology groups are somewhat technical.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] These cycles and boundaries are elements of abelian groups, and are defined in terms of the boundary homomorphisms $d_{n}:C_{n}\to C_{n-1}$ of the chain complex, where each $C_{n}$ is an abelian group, and the $d_{n}$ are group homomorphisms that satisfy $d_{n-1}\circ d_{n}=0$ for all n .
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Since such constructions are somewhat technical, informal discussions of homology sometimes focus instead on topological notions that parallel some of the group-theoretic aspects of cycles and boundaries.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] In topology, the boundary of a space is technically obtained by taking the space's closure minus its interior, but it is also a notion familiar from examples, e.g., the boundary of the unit disk is the unit circle, or more topologically, the boundary of $D^{2}$ is $S^{1}$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] In other words, $c\in C_{n}$ is a cycle if and only if $d_{n}(c)=0$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The closest topological analog of this idea would be a shape that has "no boundary," in the sense that its boundary is the empty set.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] For example, since $S^{1},S^{2}$ , and $T^{2}$ have no boundary, one can associate cycles to each of these spaces.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] However, the chain complex notion of cycles (elements whose boundary is a "zero chain") is more general than the topological notion of a shape with no boundary.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] It is this topological notion of no boundary that people generally have in mind when they claim that cycles can intuitively be thought of as detecting holes.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The idea is that for no-boundary shapes like $S^{1}$ , $S^{2}$ , and $T^{2}$ , it is possible in each case to glue on a larger shape for which the original shape is the boundary.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] For instance, starting with a circle $S^{1}$ , one could glue a 2-dimensional disk $D^{2}$ to that $S^{1}$ such that the $S^{1}$ is the boundary of that $D^{2}$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Similarly, given a two-sphere $S^{2}$ , one can glue a ball $B^{3}$ to that $S^{2}$ such that the $S^{2}$ is the boundary of that $B^{3}$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] This phenomenon is sometimes described as saying that $S^{2}$ has a $B^{3}$ -shaped "hole" or that it could be "filled in" with a $B^{3}$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] More generally, any shape with no boundary can be "filled in" with a cone, since if a given space Y has no boundary, then the boundary of the cone on Y is given by Y , and so if one "filled in" Y by gluing the cone on Y onto Y , then Y would be the boundary of that cone.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] (For example, a cone on $S^{1}$ is homeomorphic to a disk $D^{2}$ whose boundary is that $S^{1}$ .) However, it is sometimes desirable to restrict to nicer spaces such as manifolds, and not every cone is homeomorphic to a manifold.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Embedded representatives of 1-cycles, 3-cycles, and oriented 2-cycles all admit manifold-shaped holes, but for example the real projective plane $\mathbb {RP} ^{2}$ and complex projective plane $\mathbb {CP} ^{2}$ have nontrivial cobordism classes and therefore cannot be "filled in" with manifolds.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] On the other hand, the boundaries discussed in the homology of a topological space X are different from the boundaries of "filled in" holes, because the homology of a topological space X has to do with the original space X , and not with new shapes built from gluing extra pieces onto X .
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] For example, any embedded circle C in $S^{2}$ already bounds some embedded disk D in $S^{2}$ , so such C gives rise to a boundary class in the homology of $S^{2}$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] By contrast, no embedding of $S^{1}$ into one of the 2 lobes of the figure-eight shape gives a boundary, despite the fact that it is possible to glue a disk onto a figure-eight lobe.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] In other words, the elements of $H_{n}(X)$ , called *homology classes*, are equivalence classes whose representatives are n -cycles, and any two cycles are regarded as equal in $H_{n}(X)$ if and only if they differ by the addition of a boundary.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] This also implies that the "zero" element of $H_{n}(X)$ is given by the group of n -dimensional boundaries, which also includes formal sums of such boundaries.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The homology of a topological space *X* is a set of topological invariants of *X* represented by its *homology groups* $H_{0}(X),H_{1}(X),H_{2}(X),\ldots$ where the $k^{\rm {th}}$ homology group $H_{k}(X)$ describes, informally, the number of holes in *X* with a *k*-dimensional boundary.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] A 0-dimensional-boundary hole is simply a gap between two components.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Consequently, $H_{0}(X)$ describes the path-connected components of *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] A one-dimensional sphere $S^{1}$ is a circle.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] It has a single connected component and a one-dimensional-boundary hole, but no higher-dimensional holes.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The corresponding homology groups are given as $H_{k}\left(S^{1}\right)={\begin{cases}\mathbb {Z} &k=0,1\\\{0\}&{\text{otherwise}}\end{cases}}$ where $\mathbb {Z}$ is the group of integers and $\{0\}$ is the trivial group.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The group $H_{1}\left(S^{1}\right)=\mathbb {Z}$ represents a finitely-generated abelian group, with a single generator representing the one-dimensional hole contained in a circle.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] A two-dimensional sphere $S^{2}$ has a single connected component, no one-dimensional-boundary holes, a two-dimensional-boundary hole, and no higher-dimensional holes.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] A two-dimensional ball $B^{2}$ is a solid disc.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] It has a single path-connected component, but in contrast to the circle, has no higher-dimensional holes.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The corresponding homology groups are all trivial except for $H_{0}\left(B^{2}\right)=\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The torus is defined as a product of two circles $T^{2}=S^{1}\times S^{1}$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The torus has a single path-connected component, two independent one-dimensional holes (indicated by circles in red and blue) and one two-dimensional hole as the interior of the torus.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The following text describes a general algorithm for constructing the homology groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] It may be easier for the reader to look at some simple examples first: graph homology and simplicial homology.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The general construction begins with an object such as a topological space *X*, on which one first defines a *chain complex* *C*(*X*) encoding information about *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] A chain complex is a sequence of abelian groups or modules $C_{0},C_{1},C_{2},\ldots$ . connected by homomorphisms $\partial _{n}:C_{n}\to C_{n-1},$ which are called **boundary operators**.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] where 0 denotes the trivial group and $C_{i}\equiv 0$ for *i* < 0.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] It is also required that the composition of any two consecutive boundary operators be trivial.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The statement that the boundary of a boundary is trivial is equivalent to the statement that $\operatorname {im} (\partial _{n+1})\subseteq \ker(\partial _{n})$ , where $\operatorname {im} (\partial _{n+1})$ denotes the image of the boundary operator and $\ker(\partial _{n})$ its kernel.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Since each chain group *Cn* is abelian all its subgroups are normal.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Then because $\ker(\partial _{n})$ is a subgroup of *Cn*, $\ker(\partial _{n})$ is abelian, and since $\operatorname {im} (\partial _{n+1})\subseteq \ker(\partial _{n})$ therefore $\operatorname {im} (\partial _{n+1})$ is a normal subgroup of $\ker(\partial _{n})$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] called the ***n*th homology group of *X***.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The elements of *Hn*(*X*) are called **homology classes**.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Each homology class is an equivalence class over cycles and two cycles in the same homology class are said to be **homologous**.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] A chain complex is said to be exact if the image of the (*n*+1)th map is always equal to the kernel of the *n*th map.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The homology groups of *X* therefore measure "how far" the chain complex associated to *X* is from being exact.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] for a combination $\sum n_{i}\sigma _{i},$ of points $\sigma _{i},$ which are the fixed generators of *C*0.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The reduced homology groups ${\tilde {H}}_{i}(X)$ coincide with $H_{i}(X)$ for $i\neq 0.$ The extra $\mathbb {Z}$ in the chain complex represents the unique map $[\emptyset ]\longrightarrow X$ from the empty simplex to *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Computing the cycle $Z_{n}(X)$ and boundary $B_{n}(X)$ groups is usually rather difficult since they have a very large number of generators.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] On the other hand, there are tools which make the task easier.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The *simplicial homology* groups *Hn*(*X*) of a *simplicial complex* *X* are defined using the simplicial chain complex *C*(*X*), with *Cn*(*X*) the free abelian group generated by the *n*-simplices of *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The *singular homology* groups *Hn*(*X*) are defined for any topological space *X*, and agree with the simplicial homology groups for a simplicial complex.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] in analogy with the *n*th homology group.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The nth homotopy group $\pi _{n}(X)$ of a topological space X is the group of homotopy classes of basepoint-preserving maps from the n -sphere $S^{n}$ to X , under the group operation of concatenation.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The most fundamental homotopy group is the fundamental group $\pi _{1}(X)$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] For connected X , the Hurewicz theorem describes a homomorphism $h_{*}:\pi _{n}(X)\to H_{n}(X)$ called the Hurewicz homomorphism.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] For $n>1$ , this homomorphism can be complicated, but when $n=1$ , the Hurewicz homomorphism coincides with abelianization.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] That is, $h_{*}:\pi _{1}(X)\to H_{1}(X)$ is surjective and its kernel is the commutator subgroup of $\pi _{1}(X)$ , with the consequence that $H_{1}(X)$ is isomorphic to the abelianization of $\pi _{1}(X)$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Higher homotopy groups are sometimes difficult to compute.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] For instance, the homotopy groups of spheres are poorly understood and are not known in general, in contrast to the straightforward description given above for the homology groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] For an $n=1$ example, suppose X is the figure eight.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] As usual, its first homotopy group, or fundamental group, $\pi _{1}(X)$ is the group of homotopy classes of directed loops starting and ending at a predetermined point (e.g. its center).
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] It is isomorphic to the free group of rank 2, $\pi _{1}(X)\cong \mathbb {Z} *\mathbb {Z}$ , which is not commutative: looping around the lefthand cycle and then around the righthand cycle is different from looping around the righthand cycle and then looping around the lefthand cycle.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] By contrast, the figure eight's first homology group $H_{1}(X)\cong \mathbb {Z} \times \mathbb {Z}$ is abelian.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] To express this explicitly in terms of homology classes of cycles, one could take the homology class l of the lefthand cycle and the homology class r of the righthand cycle as basis elements of $H_{1}(X)$ , allowing us to write $H_{1}(X)=\{a_{l}l+a_{r}r\,|\;a_{l},a_{r}\in \mathbb {Z} \}$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The different types of homology theory arise from functors mapping from various categories of mathematical objects to the category of chain complexes.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] In each case the composition of the functor from objects to chain complexes and the functor from chain complexes to homology groups defines the overall homology functor for the theory.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The motivating example comes from algebraic topology: the **simplicial homology** of a simplicial complex *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Here the chain group *Cn* is the free abelian group or free module whose generators are the *n*-dimensional oriented simplexes of *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] which is evaluated as 0 if $n=0.$ This behavior on the generators induces a homomorphism on all of *Cn* as follows.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Given an element $c\in C_{n}$ , write it as the sum of generators ${\textstyle c=\sum _{\sigma _{i}\in X_{n}}m_{i}\sigma _{i},}$ where $X_{n}$ is the set of *n*-simplexes in *X* and the *mi* are coefficients from the ring *Cn* is defined over (usually integers, unless otherwise specified).
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The dimension of the *n*-th homology of *X* turns out to be the number of "holes" in *X* at dimension *n*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] It may be computed by putting matrix representations of these boundary mappings in Smith normal form.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Using simplicial homology example as a model, one can define a *singular homology* for any topological space *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] A chain complex for *X* is defined by taking *Cn* to be the free abelian group (or free module) whose generators are all continuous maps from *n*-dimensional simplices into *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The homomorphisms ∂*n* arise from the boundary maps of simplices.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] In abstract algebra, one uses homology to define derived functors, for example the Tor functors.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Here one starts with some covariant additive functor *F* and some module *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] By applying the functor *F* to this sequence, one obtains a chain complex; the homology $H_{n}$ of this complex depends only on *F* and *X* and is, by definition, the *n*-th derived functor of *F*, applied to *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Chain complexes form a category: A morphism from the chain complex ( $d_{n}:A_{n}\to A_{n-1}$ ) to the chain complex ( $e_{n}:B_{n}\to B_{n-1}$ ) is a sequence of homomorphisms $f_{n}:A_{n}\to B_{n}$ such that $f_{n-1}\circ d_{n}=e_{n}\circ f_{n}$ for all *n*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The *n*-th homology *Hn* can be viewed as a covariant functor from the category of chain complexes to the category of abelian groups (or modules).
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] (using the rank in the case of abelian groups and the Hamel dimension in the case of vector spaces).
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] and, especially in algebraic topology, this provides two ways to compute the important invariant $\chi$ for the object *X* which gave rise to the chain complex.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] All maps in this long exact sequence are induced by the maps between the chain complexes, except for the maps $H_{n}(C)\to H_{n-1}(A)$ The latter are called *connecting homomorphisms* and are provided by the zig-zag lemma.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] This lemma can be applied to homology in numerous ways that aid in calculating homology groups, such as the theories of relative homology and Mayer-Vietoris sequences.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] In topological data analysis, data sets are regarded as a point cloud sampling of a manifold or algebraic variety embedded in Euclidean space.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] By linking nearest neighbor points in the cloud into a triangulation, a simplicial approximation of the manifold is created and its simplicial homology may be calculated.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Finding techniques to robustly calculate homology using various triangulation strategies over multiple length scales is the topic of persistent homology.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] In sensor networks, sensors may communicate information via an ad-hoc network that dynamically changes in time.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] To understand the global context of this set of local measurements and communication paths, it is useful to compute the homology of the network topology to evaluate, for instance, holes in coverage.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] In dynamical systems theory in physics, Poincaré was one of the first to consider the interplay between the invariant manifold of a dynamical system and its topological invariants.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Morse theory relates the dynamics of a gradient flow on a manifold to, for example, its homology.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Floer homology extended this to infinite-dimensional manifolds.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The KAM theorem established that periodic orbits can follow complex trajectories; in particular, they may form braids that can be investigated using Floer homology.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] In one class of finite element methods, boundary-value problems for differential equations involving the Hodge-Laplace operator may need to be solved on topologically nontrivial domains, for example, in electromagnetic simulations.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] In these simulations, solution is aided by fixing the cohomology class of the solution based on the chosen boundary conditions and the homology of the domain.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] FEM domains can be triangulated, from which the simplicial homology can be calculated.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Various software packages have been developed for the purposes of computing homology groups of finite cell complexes.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Linbox is a C++ library for performing fast matrix operations, including Smith normal form; it interfaces with both Gap and Maple.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Chomp, CAPD::Redhom Archived 2013-07-15 at the Wayback Machine and Perseus are also written in C++.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] All three implement pre-processing algorithms based on simple-homotopy equivalence and discrete Morse theory to perform homology-preserving reductions of the input cell complexes before resorting to matrix algebra.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Kenzo is written in Lisp, and in addition to homology it may also be used to generate presentations of homotopy groups of finite simplicial complexes.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Gmsh includes a homology solver for finite element meshes, which can generate Cohomology bases directly usable by finite element software.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Homology theory can be said to start with the Euler polyhedron formula, or Euler characteristic.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] This was followed by Riemann's definition of genus and *n*-fold connectedness numerical invariants in 1857 and Betti's proof in 1871 of the independence of "homology numbers" from the choice of basis.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] On the ordinary sphere $S^{2}$ , the curve *b* in the diagram can be shrunk to the pole, and even the equatorial great circle *a* can be shrunk in the same way.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The Jordan curve theorem shows that any closed curve such as *c* can be similarly shrunk to a point.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] This implies that $S^{2}$ has trivial fundamental group, so as a consequence, it also has trivial first homology group.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The torus $T^{2}$ has closed curves which cannot be continuously deformed into each other, for example in the diagram none of the cycles *a*, *b* or *c* can be deformed into one another.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] In particular, cycles *a* and *b* cannot be shrunk to a point whereas cycle *c* can.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] If the torus surface is cut along both *a* and *b*, it can be opened out and flattened into a rectangle or, more conveniently, a square.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] One opposite pair of sides represents the cut along *a*, and the other opposite pair represents the cut along *b*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The edges of the square may then be glued back together in different ways.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The square can be twisted to allow edges to meet in the opposite direction, as shown by the arrows in the diagram.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] $K^{2}$ is the Klein bottle, which is a torus with a twist in it (In the square diagram, the twist can be seen as the reversal of the bottom arrow).
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] It is a theorem that the re-glued surface must self-intersect (when immersed in Euclidean 3-space).
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Like the torus, cycles *a* and *b* cannot be shrunk while *c* can be.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] But unlike the torus, following *b* forwards right round and back reverses left and right, because *b* happens to cross over the twist given to one join.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] If an equidistant cut on one side of *b* is made, it returns on the other side and goes round the surface a second time before returning to its starting point, cutting out a twisted Möbius strip.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Because local left and right can be arbitrarily re-oriented in this way, the surface as a whole is said to be non-orientable.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The projective plane $P^{2}$ has both joins twisted.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The uncut form, generally represented as the Boy surface, is visually complex, so a hemispherical embedding is shown in the diagram, in which antipodal points around the rim such as *A* and *A′* are identified as the same point.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Again, *a* is non-shrinkable while *c* is.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] If *b* were only wound once, it would also be non-shrinkable and reverse left and right.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] However it is wound a second time, which swaps right and left back again; it can be shrunk to a point and is homologous to *c*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Cycles can be joined or added together, as *a* and *b* on the torus were when it was cut open and flattened down.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] In the Klein bottle diagram, *a* goes round one way and −*a* goes round the opposite way.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] If *a* is thought of as a cut, then −*a* can be thought of as a gluing operation.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Making a cut and then re-gluing it does not change the surface, so *a* + (−*a*) = 0.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Since the Klein bottle is nonorientable, you can transport one of them all the way round the bottle (along the *b*-cycle), and it will come back as −*a*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] This is because the Klein bottle is made from a cylinder, whose *a*-cycle ends are glued together with opposite orientations.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Similarly, in the projective plane, following the unshrinkable cycle *b* round twice remarkably creates a trivial cycle which *can* be shrunk to a point; that is, *b* + *b* = 0.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Because *b* must be followed around twice to achieve a zero cycle, the surface is said to have a torsion coefficient of 2.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] However, following a *b*-cycle around twice in the Klein bottle gives simply *b* + *b* = 2*b*, since this cycle lives in a torsion-free homology class.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] This corresponds to the fact that in the fundamental polygon of the Klein bottle, only one pair of sides is glued with a twist, whereas in the projective plane both sides are twisted.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] A square is a contractible topological space, which implies that it has trivial homology.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Consequently, additional cuts disconnect it.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The square is not the only shape in the plane that can be glued into a surface.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Gluing opposite sides of an octagon, for example, produces a surface with two holes.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] In fact, all closed surfaces can be produced by gluing the sides of some polygon and all even-sided polygons (2*n*-gons) can be glued to make different manifolds.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Conversely, a closed surface with *n* non-zero classes can be cut into a 2*n*-gon.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Variations are also possible, for example a hexagon may also be glued to form a torus.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The first recognisable theory of homology was published by Henri Poincaré in his seminal paper "Analysis situs", *J.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The paper introduced homology classes and relations.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The possible configurations of orientable cycles are classified by the Betti numbers of the manifold (Betti numbers are a refinement of the Euler characteristic).
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Classifying the non-orientable cycles requires additional information about torsion coefficients.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The complete classification of 1- and 2-manifolds is given in the table.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Any closed 2-manifold can be realised as the connected sum of *g* tori and *c* projective planes, where the 2-sphere $S^{2}$ is regarded as the empty connected sum.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Homology is preserved by the operation of connected sum.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] In a search for increased rigour, Poincaré went on to develop the simplicial homology of a triangulated manifold and to create what is now called a simplicial chain complex.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Chain complexes (since greatly generalized) form the basis for most modern treatments of homology.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Emmy Noether and, independently, Leopold Vietoris and Walther Mayer further developed the theory of algebraic homology groups in the period 1925–28.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The new combinatorial topology formally treated topological classes as abelian groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Homology groups are finitely generated abelian groups, and homology classes are elements of these groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The Betti numbers of the manifold are the rank of the free part of the homology group, and in the special case of surfaces, the torsion part of the homology group only occurs for non-orientable cycles.
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] The subsequent spread of homology groups brought a change of terminology and viewpoint from "combinatorial topology" to "algebraic topology".
[src:algebraic-topology/homology-mathematics] Algebraic homology remains the primary method of classifying manifolds.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] In the mathematical field of algebraic topology, the **homotopy groups of spheres** describe how spheres of various dimensions can wrap around each other.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] They are examples of topological invariants, which reflect, in algebraic terms, the structure of spheres viewed as topological spaces, forgetting about their precise geometry.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The n-dimensional unit sphere — called the n-sphere for brevity, and denoted as *S**n* — generalizes the familiar circle (*S*1) and the ordinary sphere (*S*2).
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The n-sphere may be defined geometrically as the set of points in a Euclidean space of dimension *n* + 1 located at a unit distance from the origin.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The i-th *homotopy group* π*i*(*S**n*) captures the different ways in which the i-dimensional sphere *S**i* can be mapped continuously into the n-dimensional sphere *S**n*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] It does not distinguish between mappings that can be continuously deformed into one another; its elements are therefore equivalence classes of maps under homotopy.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] An addition operation makes this set of equivalence classes into an abelian group whose identity element is the class of any constant map, i.e. a one that maps all of *S**i* to a single point of *S**n*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The problem of computing the groups π*n*+*k*(*S**n*) for positive k is very difficult and of central importance to the field of algebraic topology, and as such has motivated the development of many fundamental tools and techniques.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] One early important result is the Freudenthal suspension theorem, which states that π*n*+*k*(*S**n*) is independent of n for *n* ≥ *k* + 2.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] These groups, known as the **stable homotopy groups of spheres**, can be studied using the tools of stable homotopy theory and are completely known for values of k up to 90..
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The groups in the unstable range *n* < *k* + 2 are less accessible, but have been tabulated at least for all *k* < 19.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The study of homotopy groups of spheres builds on a great deal of background material, here briefly reviewed.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Algebraic topology provides the larger context, itself built on topology and abstract algebra, with homotopy groups as a basic example.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] An ordinary sphere in three-dimensional space—the surface, not the solid ball—is just one example of what a sphere means in topology.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Geometry defines a sphere rigidly, as a shape.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] found exactly one unit away from the origin.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] This construction moves from geometry to pure topology.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] is punctured and spread flat it produces a disk; this construction repairs the puncture, like pulling a drawstring.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] , pronounced "modulo", means to take the topological space on the left (the disk) and in it join together as one all the points on the right (the circle).
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The region is 2-dimensional, which is why topology calls the resulting topological space a 2-sphere.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] , and the construction joins its ends to make a circle.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] This construction, though simple, is of great theoretical importance.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] , and sweep each point on it to one point above (the North Pole), producing the northern hemisphere, and to one point below (the South Pole), producing the southern hemisphere.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Some theory requires selecting a fixed point on the sphere, calling the pair (sphere, point) a *pointed sphere*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] For some spaces the choice matters, but for a sphere all points are equivalent so the choice is a matter of convenience.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] For spheres constructed as a repeated suspension, the point (1, 0, 0, ..., 0), which is on the equator of all the levels of suspension, works well; for the disk with collapsed rim, the point resulting from the collapse of the rim is another obvious choice.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The distinguishing feature of a topological space is its continuity structure, formalized in terms of open sets or neighborhoods.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] A continuous map is a function between spaces that preserves continuity.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] A homotopy is a continuous path between continuous maps; two maps connected by a homotopy are said to be homotopic.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The idea common to all these concepts is to discard variations that do not affect outcomes of interest.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The first homotopy group, or fundamental group, π1(*X*) of a (path connected) topological space X thus begins with continuous maps from a pointed circle (*S*1,*s*) to the pointed space (*X*,*x*), where maps from one pair to another map s into x.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] These maps (or equivalently, closed curves) are grouped together into equivalence classes based on homotopy (keeping the "base point" x fixed), so that two maps are in the same class if they are homotopic.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Just as one point is distinguished, so one class is distinguished: all maps (or curves) homotopic to the constant map *S*1↦*x* are called null homotopic.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The classes become an abstract algebraic group with the introduction of addition, defined via an "equator pinch".
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] This pinch maps the equator of a pointed sphere (here a circle) to the distinguished point, producing a "bouquet of spheres" — two pointed spheres joined at their distinguished point.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The two maps to be added map the upper and lower spheres separately, agreeing on the distinguished point, and composition with the pinch gives the sum map.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] More generally, the i-th homotopy group, π*i*(*X*) begins with the pointed i-sphere (*S**i*, *s*), and otherwise follows the same procedure.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The null homotopic class acts as the identity of the group addition, and for X equal to *S**n* (for positive n) — the homotopy groups of spheres — the groups are abelian and finitely generated.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] If for some i all maps are null homotopic, then the group π*i* consists of one element, and is called the trivial group.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] A continuous map between two topological spaces induces a group homomorphism between the associated homotopy groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] In particular, if the map is a continuous bijection (a homeomorphism), so that the two spaces have the same topology, then their i-th homotopy groups are isomorphic for all i.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] However, the real plane has exactly the same homotopy groups as a solitary point (as does a Euclidean space of any dimension), and the real plane with a point removed has the same groups as a circle, so groups alone are not enough to distinguish spaces.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Although the loss of discrimination power is unfortunate, it can also make certain computations easier.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The low-dimensional examples of homotopy groups of spheres provide a sense of the subject, because these special cases can be visualized in ordinary 3-dimensional space.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] However, such visualizations are not mathematical proofs, and do not capture the possible complexity of maps between spheres.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The simplest case concerns the ways that a circle (1-sphere) can be wrapped around another circle.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] This can be visualized by wrapping a rubber band around one's finger: it can be wrapped once, twice, three times and so on.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The wrapping can be in either of two directions, and wrappings in opposite directions will cancel out after a deformation.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The homotopy group π1(*S*1) is therefore an infinite cyclic group, and is isomorphic to the group Z of integers under addition: a homotopy class is identified with an integer by counting the number of times a mapping in the homotopy class wraps around the circle.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] This integer can also be thought of as the winding number of a loop around the origin in the plane.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The identification (a group isomorphism) of the homotopy group with the integers is often written as an equality: thus π1(*S*1) = Z.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Mappings from a 2-sphere to a 2-sphere can be visualized as wrapping a plastic bag around a ball and then sealing it.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The sealed bag is topologically equivalent to a 2-sphere, as is the surface of the ball.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The bag can be wrapped more than once by twisting it and wrapping it back over the ball.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] (There is no requirement for the continuous map to be injective and so the bag is allowed to pass through itself.) The twist can be in one of two directions and opposite twists can cancel out by deformation.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The total number of twists after cancellation is an integer, called the *degree* of the mapping.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] As in the case mappings from the circle to the circle, this degree identifies the homotopy group with the group of integers, Z.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] These two results generalize: for all *n* > 0, π*n*(*S**n*) = Z (see below).
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Any continuous mapping from a circle to an ordinary sphere can be continuously deformed to a one-point mapping, and so its homotopy class is trivial.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] One way to visualize this is to imagine a rubber-band wrapped around a frictionless ball: the band can always be slid off the ball.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The homotopy group is therefore a trivial group, with only one element, the identity element, and so it can be identified with the subgroup of Z consisting only of the number zero.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Showing this rigorously requires more care, however, due to the existence of space-filling curves.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] This result generalizes to higher dimensions.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] All mappings from a lower-dimensional sphere into a sphere of higher dimension are similarly trivial: if *i* < *n*, then π*i*(*S**n*) = 0.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] This can be shown as a consequence of the cellular approximation theorem.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] All the interesting cases of homotopy groups of spheres involve mappings from a higher-dimensional sphere onto one of lower dimension.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Unfortunately, the only example which can easily be visualized is not interesting: there are no nontrivial mappings from the ordinary sphere to the circle.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] This is because *S*1 has the real line as its universal cover which is contractible (it has the homotopy type of a point).
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] In addition, because *S*2 is simply connected, by the lifting criterion, any map from *S*2 to *S*1 can be lifted to a map into the real line and the nullhomotopy descends to the downstairs space (via composition).
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The first nontrivial example with *i* > *n* concerns mappings from the 3-sphere to the ordinary 2-sphere, and was discovered by Heinz Hopf, who constructed a nontrivial map from *S*3 to *S*2, now known as the Hopf fibration.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] This map generates the homotopy group π3(*S*2) = Z.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] In the late 19th century Camille Jordan introduced the notion of homotopy and used the notion of a homotopy group, without using the language of group theory.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] A more rigorous approach was adopted by Henri Poincaré in his 1895 set of papers *Analysis situs* where the related concepts of homology and the fundamental group were also introduced.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Higher homotopy groups were first defined by Eduard Čech in 1932.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] An important method for calculating the various groups is the concept of stable algebraic topology, which finds properties that are independent of the dimensions.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Typically these only hold for larger dimensions.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The first such result was Hans Freudenthal's suspension theorem, published in 1937.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Stable algebraic topology flourished between 1945 and 1966 with many important results.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Whitehead showed that there is a metastable range for the homotopy groups of spheres.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Jean-Pierre Serre used spectral sequences to show that most of these groups are finite, the exceptions being π*n*(*S**n*) and π4*n*−1(*S*2*n*).
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Others who worked in this area included José Adem, Hiroshi Toda, Frank Adams, J.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Peter May, Mark Mahowald, Daniel Isaksen, Guozhen Wang, and Zhouli Xu.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The stable homotopy groups π*n*+*k*(*S**n*) are known for k up to 90, and, as of 2023, unknown for larger k.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] As noted already, when i is less than n, π*i*(*S**n*) = 0, the trivial group.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The reason is that a continuous mapping from an i-sphere to an n-sphere with *i* < *n* can always be deformed so that it is not surjective.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Consequently, its image is contained in *S**n* with a point removed; this is a contractible space, and any mapping to such a space can be deformed into a one-point mapping.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] When *i* = *n*, π*n*(*S**n*) = Z, the infinite cyclic group, generated by the identity map from the n-sphere to itself.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] It follows from the definition of homotopy groups that the identity map and its multiples are elements of π*n*(*S**n*).
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] That these are the only elements can be shown using the Freudenthal suspension theorem, which relates the homotopy groups of a space and its suspension.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] In the case of spheres, the suspension of an n-sphere is an (*n*+1)-sphere, and the suspension theorem states that there is a group homomorphism π*i*(*S**n*) → π*i*+1(*S**n*+1) which is an isomorphism for all *i* < 2*n*-1 and is surjective for *i* = 2*n*-1.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] in which the first homomorphism is a surjection and the rest are isomorphisms.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] As noted already, π1(*S*1) = Z, and π2(*S*2) contains a copy of Z generated by the identity map, so the fact that there is a surjective homomorphism from π1(*S*1) to π2(*S*2) implies that π2(*S*2) = Z.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The rest of the homomorphisms in the sequence are isomorphisms, so π*n*(*S**n*) = Z for all n.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The homology groups *H**i*(*S**n*), with *i* > *n*, are all trivial, which suggests that the corresponding homotopy groups might be trivial too.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] However, the corresponding homotopy groups are not trivial in general.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] This is the case that is of real importance: the higher homotopy groups π*i*(*S**n*), for *i* > *n*, are surprisingly complex and difficult to compute, and the effort to compute them has generated a significant amount of new mathematics.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The following table gives an idea of the complexity of the higher homotopy groups even for spheres of dimension 8 or less.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] In this table, the entries are either a) the trivial group 0, the infinite cyclic group Z, b) the finite cyclic groups of order n (written as Z*n*), or c) the direct products of such groups (written, for example, as Z24×Z3 or Z2 2 = Z2×Z2).
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Extended tables of homotopy groups of spheres are given at the end of the article.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The first row of this table is straightforward.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The homotopy groups π*i*(*S*1) of the 1-sphere are trivial for *i* > 1, because the universal covering space, $\mathbb {R}$ , which has the same higher homotopy groups, is contractible.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Beyond the first row, the higher homotopy groups (*i* > *n*) appear to be chaotic, but in fact there are many patterns, some obvious and some very subtle.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] These patterns follow from many different theoretical results.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The fact that the groups below the jagged line in the table above are constant along the diagonals is explained by the suspension theorem of Hans Freudenthal, which implies that the suspension homomorphism from π*n*+*k*(*S**n*) to π*n*+*k*+1(*S**n*+1) is an isomorphism for *n* > *k* + 1.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The groups π*n*+*k*(*S**n*) with *n* > *k* + 1 are called the *stable homotopy groups of spheres*, and are denoted π*S* *k*: they are finite abelian groups for *k* ≠ 0, and have been computed in numerous cases, although the general pattern is still elusive.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] For *n* ≤ *k*+1, the groups are called the *unstable homotopy groups of spheres*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] For this specific bundle, each group homomorphism π*i*(*S*1) → π*i*(*S*3), induced by the inclusion *S*1 → *S*3, maps all of π*i*(*S*1) to zero, since the lower-dimensional sphere *S*1 can be deformed to a point inside the higher-dimensional one *S*3.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] This corresponds to the vanishing of π1(*S*3).
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Since π*i*−1(*S*1) vanishes for i at least 3, the first row shows that π*i*(*S*2) and π*i*(*S*3) are isomorphic whenever i is at least 3, as observed above.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The Hopf fibration may be constructed as follows: pairs of complex numbers (*z*0,*z*1) with |*z*0|2 + |*z*1|2 = 1 form a 3-sphere, and their ratios ⁠*z*0/*z*1⁠ cover the complex plane plus infinity, a 2-sphere.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The Hopf map *S*3 → *S*2 sends any such pair to its ratio.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] constructed using pairs of quaternions or octonions instead of complex numbers.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Thus the long exact sequences again break into families of split short exact sequences, implying two families of relations.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The three fibrations have base space *S**n* with *n* = 2*m*, for *m* = 1, 2, 3.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] A fibration does exist for *S*1 (*m* = 0) as mentioned above, but not for *S*16 (*m* = 4) and beyond.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] the first non-trivial case of the Hopf invariant one problem, because such a fibration would imply that the failed relation is true.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Homotopy groups of spheres are closely related to cobordism classes of manifolds.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] In 1938 Lev Pontryagin established an isomorphism between the homotopy group π*n*+*k*(*S**n*) and the group Ωframed *k*(*S**n*+*k*) of cobordism classes of differentiable k-submanifolds of *S**n*+*k* which are "framed", i.e. have a trivialized normal bundle.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] For example, π*n*(*S**n*) = Z is the cobordism group of framed 0-dimensional submanifolds of *S**n*, computed by the algebraic sum of their points, corresponding to the degree of maps *f* : *S**n* → *S**n*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The projection of the Hopf fibration *S*3 → *S*2 represents a generator of π3(*S*2) = Ωframed 1(*S*3) = Z which corresponds to the framed 1-dimensional submanifold of *S*3 defined by the standard embedding *S*1 ⊂ *S*3 with a nonstandard trivialization of the normal 2-plane bundle.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Until the advent of more sophisticated algebraic methods in the early 1950s (Serre) the Pontrjagin isomorphism was the main tool for computing the homotopy groups of spheres.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] In 1954 the Pontrjagin isomorphism was generalized by René Thom to an isomorphism expressing other groups of cobordism classes (e.g. of all manifolds) as homotopy groups of spaces and spectra.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] In more recent work the argument is usually reversed, with cobordism groups computed in terms of homotopy groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] In 1951, Jean-Pierre Serre showed that homotopy groups of spheres are all finite except for those of the form π*n*(*S**n*) or π4*n*−1(*S*2*n*) (for positive n), when the group is the product of the infinite cyclic group with a finite abelian group.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] In particular the homotopy groups are determined by their p-components for all primes p.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The 2-components are hardest to calculate, and in several ways behave differently from the p-components for odd primes.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] In the same paper, Serre found the first place that p-torsion occurs in the homotopy groups of n dimensional spheres, by showing that π*n*+*k*(*S**n*) has no p-torsion if *k* < 2*p* − 3, and has a unique subgroup of order p if *n* ≥ 3 and *k* = 2*p* − 3.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The case of 2-dimensional spheres is slightly different: the first p-torsion occurs for *k* = 2*p* − 3 + 1.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] In the case of odd torsion there are more precise results; in this case there is a big difference between odd and even dimensional spheres.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] If p is an odd prime and *n* = 2*i* + 1, then elements of the p-component of π*n*+*k*(*S**n*) have order at most *p**i*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] This is in some sense the best possible result, as these groups are known to have elements of this order for some values of k.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Furthermore, the stable range can be extended in this case: if n is odd then the double suspension from π*k*(*S**n*) to π*k*+2(*S**n*+2) is an isomorphism of p-components if *k* < *p*(*n* + 1) − 3, and an epimorphism if equality holds.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The p-torsion of the intermediate group π*k*+1(*S**n*+1) can be strictly larger.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] (where (*p*) means take the p-component).
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] This exact sequence is similar to the ones coming from the Hopf fibration; the difference is that it works for all even-dimensional spheres, albeit at the expense of ignoring 2-torsion.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Combining the results for odd and even dimensional spheres shows that much of the odd torsion of unstable homotopy groups is determined by the odd torsion of the stable homotopy groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] For stable homotopy groups there are more precise results about p-torsion.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] For example, if *k* < 2*p*(*p* − 1) − 2 for a prime p then the p-primary component of the stable homotopy group πS *k* vanishes unless *k* + 1 is divisible by 2(*p* − 1), in which case it is cyclic of order p.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] An important subgroup of π*n*+*k*(*S**n*), for *k* ≥ 2, is the image of the J-homomorphism *J* : π*k*(SO(*n*)) → π*n*+*k*(*S**n*), where SO(*n*) denotes the special orthogonal group.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] In the stable range *n* ≥ *k* + 2, the homotopy groups π*k*(SO(*n*)) only depend on *k* (mod 8).
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] This last case accounts for the elements of unusually large finite order in π*n*+*k*(*S**n*) for such values of k.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] For example, the stable groups π*n*+11(*S**n*) have a cyclic subgroup of order 504, the denominator of ⁠*B*6/12⁠ = ⁠1/504⁠.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The stable homotopy groups of spheres are the direct sum of the image of the J-homomorphism, and the kernel of the Adams e-invariant, a homomorphism from these groups to $\mathbb {Q} /\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Roughly speaking, the image of the J-homomorphism is the subgroup of "well understood" or "easy" elements of the stable homotopy groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] These well understood elements account for most elements of the stable homotopy groups of spheres in small dimensions.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The quotient of πS *n* by the image of the J-homomorphism is considered to be the "hard" part of the stable homotopy groups of spheres (Adams 1966).
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] (Adams also introduced certain order 2 elements μ*n* of πS *n* for *n* ≡ 1 or 2 (mod 8), and these are also considered to be "well understood".) Tables of homotopy groups of spheres sometimes omit the "easy" part im(*J*) to save space.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] of the stable homotopy groups of spheres is a supercommutative graded ring, where multiplication is given by composition of representing maps, and any element of non-zero degree is nilpotent; the nilpotence theorem on complex cobordism implies Nishida's theorem.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Example: If η is the generator of πS 1 (of order 2), then *η*2 is nonzero and generates πS 2, and *η*3 is nonzero and 12 times a generator of πS 3, while *η*4 is zero because the group πS 4 is trivial.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] If f and g and h are elements of πS * with *f* *g* = 0 and *g*⋅*h* = 0, there is a Toda bracket ⟨*f*, *g*, *h*⟩ of these elements.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The Toda bracket is not quite an element of a stable homotopy group, because it is only defined up to addition of products of certain other elements.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Hiroshi Toda used the composition product and Toda brackets to label many of the elements of homotopy groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] There are also higher Toda brackets of several elements, defined when suitable lower Toda brackets vanish.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] This parallels the theory of Massey products in cohomology.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Every element of the stable homotopy groups of spheres can be expressed using composition products and higher Toda brackets in terms of certain well known elements, called Hopf elements.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] If X is any finite simplicial complex with finite fundamental group, in particular if X is a sphere of dimension at least 2, then its homotopy groups are all finitely generated abelian groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] To compute these groups, they are often factored into their p-components for each prime p, and calculating each of these p-groups separately.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The first few homotopy groups of spheres can be computed using ad hoc variations of the ideas above; beyond this point, most methods for computing homotopy groups of spheres are based on spectral sequences.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] This is usually done by constructing suitable fibrations and taking the associated long exact sequences of homotopy groups; spectral sequences are a systematic way of organizing the complicated information that this process generates.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The computation of the homotopy groups of *S*2 has been reduced to a combinatorial group theory question.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] (2006) identify these homotopy groups as certain quotients of the Brunnian braid groups of *S*2.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Under this correspondence, every nontrivial element in π*n*(*S*2) for *n* > 2 may be represented by a Brunnian braid over *S*2 that is not Brunnian over the disk *D*2.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] For example, the Hopf map *S*3 → *S*2 corresponds to the Borromean rings.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] , in which case the image has index 1 or 2.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] Tables of homotopy groups of spheres are most conveniently organized by showing π*n*+*k*(*S**n*).
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The following table shows many of the groups π*n*+*k*(*S**n*).
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The stable homotopy groups are highlighted in blue, the unstable ones in red.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The stable homotopy groups π*S* *k* are the products of cyclic groups of the infinite or prime power orders shown in the table.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy-groups-of-spheres] The mod 8 behavior of the table comes from Bott periodicity via the J-homomorphism, whose image is underlined.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] A notable use of homotopy is the definition of homotopy groups and cohomotopy groups, important invariants in algebraic topology.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] In practice, there are technical difficulties in using homotopies with certain spaces.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Algebraic topologists work with compactly generated spaces, CW complexes, or spectra.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] If we think of the second parameter of *H* as time, then *H* describes a *continuous deformation* of *f* into *g*: at time 0, we have the function *f*, and at time 1, we have the function *g*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] We can also think of the second parameter as a "slider control" that allows us to smoothly transition from *f* to *g* as the slider moves from 0 to 1, and vice versa.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] An alternative notation is to say that a homotopy between two continuous functions $f,g:X\to Y$ is a family of continuous functions $h_{t}:X\to Y$ for $t\in [0,1]$ such that $h_{0}=f$ and $h_{1}=g$ , and the map $(x,t)\mapsto h_{t}(x)$ is continuous from $X\times [0,1]$ to Y .
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] The two versions coincide by setting $h_{t}(x)=H(x,t)$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] It is not sufficient to require each map $h_{t}(x)$ to be continuous.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] The animation that is looped above right provides an example of a homotopy between two embeddings, *f* and *g*, of the torus into *R*3.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] *X* is the torus, *Y* is *R*3, *f* is some continuous function from the torus to *R*3 that takes the torus to the embedded surface-of-a-doughnut shape with which the animation starts; *g* is some continuous function that takes the torus to the embedded surface-of-a-coffee-mug shape.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] The animation shows the image of *h**t*(X) as a function of the parameter *t*, where *t* varies with time from 0 to 1 over each cycle of the animation loop.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] It pauses, then shows the image as *t* varies back from 1 to 0, pauses, and repeats this cycle.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Continuous functions *f* and *g* are said to be homotopic if and only if there is a homotopy *H* taking *f* to *g* as described above.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Being homotopic is an equivalence relation on the set of all continuous functions from *X* to *Y*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] This homotopy relation is compatible with function composition in the following sense: if *f*1, *g*1 : *X* → *Y* are homotopic, and *f*2, *g*2 : *Y* → *Z* are homotopic, then their compositions *f*2 ∘ *f*1 and *g*2 ∘ *g*1 : *X* → *Z* are also homotopic.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Given two topological spaces *X* and *Y*, a **homotopy equivalence** between *X* and *Y* is a pair of continuous maps *f* : *X* → *Y* and *g* : *Y* → *X*, such that *g* ∘ *f* is homotopic to the identity map id*X* and *f* ∘ *g* is homotopic to id*Y*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] If such a pair exists, then *X* and *Y* are said to be **homotopy equivalent**, or of the same **homotopy type**.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] This relation of homotopy equivalence is often denoted $\simeq$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Intuitively, two spaces *X* and *Y* are homotopy equivalent if they can be transformed into one another by bending, shrinking and expanding operations.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Spaces that are homotopy equivalent to a point are called contractible.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] A homeomorphism is a special case of a homotopy equivalence, in which *g* ∘ *f* is equal to the identity map id*X* (not only homotopic to it), and *f* ∘ *g* is equal to id*Y*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Therefore, if X and Y are homeomorphic, then they are homotopy equivalent, but the opposite is not true.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] A function f is said to be **null-homotopic** if it is homotopic to a constant function.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] (The homotopy from f to a constant function is then sometimes called a **null-homotopy**.) For example, a map f from the unit circle $S^{1}$ to any space X is null-homotopic precisely when it can be continuously extended to a map from the unit disk $D^{2}$ to X that agrees with f on the boundary.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] It follows from these definitions that a space X is contractible if and only if the identity map from X to itself—which is always a homotopy equivalence—is null-homotopic.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Homotopy equivalence is important because in algebraic topology many concepts are **homotopy invariant**, that is, they respect the relation of homotopy equivalence.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] An example of an algebraic invariant of topological spaces which is not homotopy invariant is compactly supported homology (which is, roughly speaking, the homology of the compactification, and compactification is not homotopy invariant).
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] In order to define the fundamental group, one needs the notion of **homotopy relative to a subspace**.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] These are homotopies which keep the elements of the subspace fixed.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Also, if *g* is a retraction from *X* to *K* and *f* is the identity map, this is known as a strong deformation retract of *X* to *K*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] When *K* is a point, the term **pointed homotopy** is used.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] since one cannot be deformed into the other through a continuous path of homeomorphisms of the ambient space.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] When two given continuous functions *f* and *g* from the topological space *X* to the topological space *Y* are embeddings, one can ask whether they can be connected 'through embeddings'.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] This gives rise to the concept of **isotopy**, which is a homotopy, *H*, in the notation used before, such that for each fixed *t*, *H*(*x*, *t*) gives an embedding.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] A related, but separate, concept is that of ambient isotopy.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Requiring that two embeddings be isotopic is a stronger requirement than that they be homotopic.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] For example, the map from the interval [−1, 1] into the real numbers defined by *f*(*x*) = −*x* is *not* isotopic to the identity *g*(*x*) = *x*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Any homotopy from *f* to the identity would have to exchange the endpoints, which would mean that they would have to 'pass through' each other.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Moreover, *f* has changed the orientation of the interval and *g* has not, which is impossible under an isotopy.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Two homeomorphisms (which are special cases of embeddings) of the unit ball which agree on the boundary can be shown to be isotopic using Alexander's trick.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] For this reason, the map of the unit disc in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ defined by *f*(*x*, *y*) = (−*x*, −*y*) is isotopic to a 180-degree rotation around the origin, and so the identity map and *f* are isotopic because they can be connected by rotations.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] In geometric topology—for example, in knot theory—the idea of isotopy is used to construct equivalence relations.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] For example, when should two knots be considered the same?
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] We take two knots, *K*1 and *K*2, in three-dimensional space.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] A knot is an embedding of a one-dimensional space, the "loop of string" (or the circle), into this space, and this embedding gives a homeomorphism between the circle and its image in the embedding space.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] One may try to define knot equivalence based on isotopy instead of the more restricted property of ambient isotopy.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] That is, two knots are isotopic when there exists a continuous function starting at *t* = 0 giving the *K*1 embedding, ending at *t* = 1 giving the *K*2 embedding, with all intermediate values corresponding to embeddings.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] However, this definition would make every knot equivalent to the unknot, as the knotted portions can be "contracted" down to a straight line.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] The problem is that, while continuous, this is not an injective function of the Euclidean space that the knot is embedded in.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] An ambient isotopy, studied in this context, is an isotopy of the larger space, considered in light of its action on the embedded submanifold.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Knots *K*1 and *K*2 are considered equivalent when there is a continuous [0, 1]-indexed family of maps which moves *K*1 to *K*2 via homeomorphisms of the Euclidean space.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Similar language is used for the equivalent concept in contexts where one has a stronger notion of equivalence.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] For example, a path between two smooth embeddings is a **smooth isotopy**.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] On a Lorentzian manifold, certain curves are distinguished as timelike (representing something that only goes forwards, not backwards, in time, in every local frame).
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] A timelike homotopy between two timelike curves is a homotopy such that the curve remains timelike during the continuous transformation from one curve to another.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] No closed timelike curve (CTC) on a Lorentzian manifold is timelike homotopic to a point (that is, null timelike homotopic); such a manifold is therefore said to be multiply connected by timelike curves.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] A manifold such as the 3-sphere can be simply connected (by any type of curve), and yet be timelike multiply connected.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] The homotopy lifting property is used to characterize fibrations.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Another useful property involving homotopy is the homotopy extension property, which characterizes the extension of a homotopy between two functions from a subset of some set to the set itself.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] It is useful when dealing with cofibrations.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Since the relation of two functions $f,g\colon X\to Y$ being homotopic relative to a subspace is an equivalence relation, we can look at the equivalence classes of maps between a fixed *X* and *Y*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] If we fix $X=[0,1]^{n}$ , the unit interval [0, 1] crossed with itself *n* times, and we take its boundary $\partial ([0,1]^{n})$ as a subspace, then the equivalence classes form a group, denoted $\pi _{n}(Y,y_{0})$ , where $y_{0}$ is in the image of the subspace $\partial ([0,1]^{n})$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] We can define the action of one equivalence class on another, and so we get a group.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] These groups are called the homotopy groups.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] In the case $n=1$ , it is also called the fundamental group.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] The idea of homotopy can be turned into a formal category of category theory.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] The **homotopy category** is the category whose objects are topological spaces, and whose morphisms are homotopy equivalence classes of continuous maps.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Two topological spaces *X* and *Y* are isomorphic in this category if and only if they are homotopy equivalent.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Then a functor on the category of topological spaces is homotopy invariant if it can be expressed as a functor on the homotopy category.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] For example, homology groups are a *functorial* homotopy invariant: this means that if *f* and *g* from *X* to *Y* are homotopic, then the group homomorphisms induced by *f* and *g* on the level of homology groups are the same: H*n*(*f*) = H*n*(*g*) : H*n*(*X*) → H*n*(*Y*) for all *n*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Likewise, if *X* and *Y* are in addition path-connected, and the homotopy between *f* and *g* is pointed, then the group homomorphisms induced by *f* and *g* on the level of homotopy groups are also the same: π*n*(*f*) = π*n*(*g*) : π*n*(*X*) → π*n*(*Y*).
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Based on the concept of the homotopy, computation methods for algebraic and differential equations have been developed.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] The methods for algebraic equations include the homotopy continuation method and the continuation method (see numerical continuation).
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] The methods for differential equations include the homotopy analysis method.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Homotopy theory can be used as a foundation for homology theory: one can represent a cohomology functor on a space *X* by mappings of *X* into an appropriate fixed space, up to homotopy equivalence.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] For example, for any abelian group *G*, and any based CW-complex *X*, the set $[X,K(G,n)]$ of based homotopy classes of based maps from *X* to the Eilenberg–MacLane space $K(G,n)$ is in natural bijection with the *n*-th singular cohomology group $H^{n}(X,G)$ of the space *X*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] One says that the omega-spectrum of Eilenberg-MacLane spaces are representing spaces for singular cohomology with coefficients in *G*.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Using this fact, homotopy classes between a CW complex and a multiply connected space can be calculated using cohomology as described by the Hopf–Whitney theorem.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Recently, homotopy theory is used to develop deep learning-based generative models like diffusion models and flow-based generative models.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Perturbing the complex non-Gaussian states is a tough task.
[src:algebraic-topology/homotopy] Using deep learning and homotopy, such complex states can be transformed to Gaussian state and mildly perturbed to get transformed back to perturbed complex states.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] In mathematics, a **simplicial complex** is a structured set of *simplices* (for example, points, line segments, triangles, and their *n*-dimensional counterparts) such that all the faces and intersections of the elements are also included in the set (see illustration).
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] To distinguish a simplicial complex from an abstract simplicial complex, the former is often called a **geometric simplicial complex**.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] The non-empty intersection of any two simplices $\sigma _{1},\sigma _{2}\in {\mathcal {K}}$ is a face of both $\sigma _{1}$ and $\sigma _{2}$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] See also the definition of an abstract simplicial complex, which loosely speaking is a simplicial complex without an associated geometry.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] A **simplicial *k*-complex** ${\mathcal {K}}$ is a simplicial complex where the largest dimension of any simplex in ${\mathcal {K}}$ equals *k*.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] For instance, a simplicial 2-complex must contain at least one triangle, and must not contain any tetrahedra or higher-dimensional simplices.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] A **pure** or **homogeneous** simplicial *k*-complex ${\mathcal {K}}$ is a simplicial complex where every simplex of dimension less than *k* is a face of some simplex $\sigma \in {\mathcal {K}}$ of dimension exactly *k*.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] Informally, a pure 1-complex "looks" like it's made of a bunch of lines, a 2-complex "looks" like it's made of a bunch of triangles, etc.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] An example of a *non*-homogeneous complex is a triangle with a line segment attached to one of its vertices.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] Pure simplicial complexes can be thought of as triangulations and provide a definition of polytopes.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] A **facet** is a maximal simplex, i.e., any simplex in a complex that is *not* a face of any larger simplex.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] (Note the difference from a "face" of a simplex).
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] A pure simplicial complex can be thought of as a complex where all facets have the same dimension.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] For (boundary complexes of) simplicial polytopes this coincides with the meaning from polyhedral combinatorics.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] Sometimes the term *face* is used to refer to a simplex of a complex, not to be confused with a face of a simplex.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] For a simplicial complex embedded in a *k*-dimensional space, the *k*-faces are sometimes referred to as its **cells**.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] The term *cell* is sometimes used in a broader sense to denote a set homeomorphic to a simplex, leading to the definition of cell complex.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] The **underlying space**, sometimes called the **carrier** of a simplicial complex, is the union of its simplices.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] The relative interiors of all simplices in ${\mathcal {K}}$ form a partition of its underlying space $|{\mathcal {K}}|$ : for each point $x\in |{\mathcal {K}}|$ , there is exactly one simplex in ${\mathcal {K}}$ containing x in its relative interior.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] This simplex is called the **support** of *x* and denoted $\operatorname {supp} (x)$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] Let *K* be a simplicial complex and let *S* be a collection of simplices in *K*.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] The **closure** of *S* (denoted $\mathrm {Cl} \ S$ ) is the smallest simplicial subcomplex of *K* that contains each simplex in *S*. $\mathrm {Cl} \ S$ is obtained by repeatedly adding to *S* each face of every simplex in *S*.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] The **star** of *S* (denoted $\mathrm {st} \ S$ ) is the union of the stars of each simplex in *S*.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] For a single simplex *s*, the star of *s* is the set of simplices in *K* that have *s* as a face.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] The star of *S* is generally not a simplicial complex itself, so some authors define the **closed star** of S (denoted $\mathrm {St} \ S$ ) as $\mathrm {Cl} \ \mathrm {st} \ S$ the closure of the star of S.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] It is the closed star of *S* minus the stars of all faces of *S*.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] In algebraic topology, simplicial complexes are often useful for concrete calculations.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] For the definition of homology groups of a simplicial complex, one can read the corresponding chain complex directly, provided that consistent orientations are made of all simplices.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] The requirements of homotopy theory lead to the use of more general spaces, the CW complexes.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] Infinite complexes are a technical tool basic in algebraic topology.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] In algebraic topology, a compact topological space which is homeomorphic to the geometric realization of a finite simplicial complex is usually called a polyhedron (see Spanier 1966, Maunder 1996, Hilton & Wylie 1967).
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] Combinatorialists often study the ***f*-vector** of a simplicial d-complex Δ, which is the integer sequence $(f_{0},f_{1},f_{2},\ldots ,f_{d+1})$ , where *f**i* is the number of (*i*−1)-dimensional faces of Δ (by convention, *f*0 = 1 unless Δ is the empty complex).
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] For instance, if Δ is the boundary of the octahedron, then its *f*-vector is (1, 6, 12, 8), and if Δ is the first simplicial complex pictured above, its *f*-vector is (1, 18, 23, 8, 1).
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] A complete characterization of the possible *f*-vectors of simplicial complexes is given by the Kruskal–Katona theorem.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] By using the *f*-vector of a simplicial *d*-complex Δ as coefficients of a polynomial (written in decreasing order of exponents), we obtain the **f-polynomial** of Δ.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] Combinatorists are often quite interested in the **h-vector** of a simplicial complex Δ, which is the sequence of coefficients of the polynomial that results from plugging *x* − 1 into the *f*-polynomial of Δ.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] So the *h*-vector of the boundary of the octahedron is (1, 3, 3, 1).
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] It is not an accident this *h*-vector is symmetric.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] In fact, this happens whenever Δ is the boundary of a simplicial polytope (these are the Dehn–Sommerville equations).
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] In general, however, the *h*-vector of a simplicial complex is not even necessarily positive.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] For instance, if we take Δ to be the 2-complex given by two triangles intersecting only at a common vertex, the resulting *h*-vector is (1, 3, −2).
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] A complete characterization of all simplicial polytope *h*-vectors is given by the celebrated g-theorem of Stanley, Billera, and Lee.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] A triangulation of a topological space X is a homeomorphism $t:|{\mathcal {T}}|\rightarrow X$ where ${\mathcal {T}}$ is a simplicial complex.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] Topological spaces do not necessarily admit a triangulation and if they do, it is never unique.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] Topological manifolds of dimension $d\leq 3$ are always triangulable, but not necessarily for $d>3$ .
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] Differentiable manifolds of any dimension $d\geq 1$ admit triangulations.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] Any abstract d -dimensional simplicial complex can be embedded in a $(2d+1)$ -dimensional space.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] This result is piecewise linear counterpart of the (weak) Whitney embedding theorem.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] The simplicial complex recognition problem is: given a finite simplicial complex, decide whether it is homeomorphic to a given geometric object.
[src:algebraic-topology/simplicial-complex] This problem is undecidable for any *d*-dimensional manifolds for $d\geq 5$ .
